Today, President Abdel Fattah El-Sisi received a phone call from Pedro S√°nchez, the Prime Minister of Spain, which is holding the rotating Presidency of the Council of the European Union. The call focused on the developments in the Gaza Strip. President El-Sisi and the Spanish Prime Minister expressed deep concern with regard to the ongoing escalation of violence and the gravely deteriorating security and humanitarian situations in the Strip. They emphasized the need to coordinate international efforts to urge the parties to adopt the path of de-escalation so as to prevent the loss of more innocent civilian lives and prevent the security repercussions of the conflict from expanding to the entire region. President El-sisi reiterated the need for concerted efforts by the international community to ensure the delivery of humanitarian services and aid to the Palestinian people in the Gaza Strip, and to strengthen efforts toward addressing the root-causes of the escalation, by achieving a just, comprehensive and lasting solution to the Palestinian cause.

On this day in 1777, British General John Burgoyne surrenders his army at Saratoga. It was an astounding American victory, and it changed the course of the Revolution! Months earlier, Burgoyne had come to America with a bold mission: His army was supposed to break the back of the American Revolution by cutting off the New England colonies from the southern ones. Unfortunately for the British, Americans chipped away at the size and strength of Burgoyne‚Äôs force during the summer of 1777. Delays caused the British to run low on supplies. Burgoyne won some victories, but he was losing too many men. By October 7, Burgoyne was in a bad position. He had been waiting for reinforcements from General Sir Henry Clinton, but to no avail. He probably should have retreated, but he decided to attack instead. It was a disaster! By the end of the day, the British were badly beaten and retreating toward one of their redoubts. The next day, the British buried one of their fallen leaders at the Great Redoubt. Then they immediately began to retreat north, to an area near Saratoga which had been previously fortified. The retreat was painfully slow, with many stops. Once the British reached their destination, apparently some soldiers were so exhausted that they lay down on the ground and fell asleep in their wet clothes, even as rain fell on top of them. Burgoyne has been criticized for not forcing the retreat further‚Äîand faster! Would he have been able to get away if he had? Americans were slow to begin their pursuit of the British, but they moved quickly once they got started. Before too long, Burgoyne was completely surrounded. On October 13, Burgoyne conceded that he would need to work out terms for a surrender. A few days later, an agreement was finally reached; Burgoyne formally surrendered to Gates on October 17. One British officer later wrote of his experience as he lay down arms. Americans had stayed within their lines, so as not to add to the British humiliation. ‚ÄúI did not observe the least disrespect, or even a taunting look,‚Äù the British officer wrote, ‚Äúbut all was mute astonishment and pity.‚Äù As General Burgoyne handed his sword to American General Horatio Gates, he made a comment that was later reported in various ways. Burgoyne said something to this effect: ‚ÄúThe fortune of war, General Gates, has made me your prisoner.‚Äù Gates responded, simply: ‚ÄúI shall always be ready to bear testimony that it has not been through any fault of your excellency.‚Äù Many historians consider the Battle of Saratoga to be one of the most important battles ever fought. Americans had proven to the world that they could hold their own against the powerful British army! When France learned of the victory, it prodded that country into signing a treaty with us. The Spanish and Dutch would soon also join the effort. The entry of these countries into the conflict made the war more global; thus, British resources had to be stretched even further. Obviously, that could only help us in our own fight for independence. We would finally win that fight almost 4 years to the day after Burgoyne‚Äôs surrender. ‚ÄúGiggles‚Äù In the heart of the Enchanted Forest, where the leaves whispered secrets and the flowers danced to the rhythm of the wind, there lived a faerie named Giggles. Giggles was unlike any other faerie in the forest, for she possessed a unique gift. She treated laughter as the most potent healing balm. Giggles had a contagious laugh that could brighten the darkest of days. Her wings shimmered like a rainbow, and her eyes sparkled with mischief. She understood the magic of laughter, the way it could mend even the deepest wounds and bridge the widest gaps. One day, a great sadness befell the Enchanted Forest. A bitter feud had erupted between the sprites and the gnomes over a patch of enchanted mushrooms. The forest was no longer harmonious, and the once-lively creatures now wore somber expressions. Giggles decided it was time to put her extraordinary gift to use. She fluttered down to where the sprites and gnomes were locked in an argument and began to giggle. At first, they stared at her, puzzled and a bit annoyed. But Giggles persisted, her laughter growing more infectious by the moment. Slowly, a sprite couldn‚Äôt help but chuckle, and a gnome‚Äôs stern face broke into a smile. Giggles‚Äô laughter spread like wildfire, and soon, all the creatures, sprites and gnomes alike, were laughing together. As the laughter filled the forest, something magical happened. The mushrooms, which had been the source of the conflict, began to glow with a radiant light. The forest itself seemed to vibrate with joy, and the discord melted away. Giggles had brought balance to the Enchanted Forest through her broad perspective and the power of laughter. She showed everyone that even the most challenging situations could be eased with a good dose of humor and a shared laugh. From that day on, Giggles became the forest‚Äôs peacemaker. She traveled far and wide, bringing her laughter to every corner of the enchanted realm, healing rifts, and renewing friendships. The Enchanted Forest, once again, thrived in harmony, all thanks to the faerie named Giggles, who believed that laughter was the most powerful magic of all.

It is so great we are having conversations about the mental load... There has been so much chat about my interview the other day in which Fitzy & Wippa With Kate Ritchie and I talked about the mental load. Unfortunately, when you get a 90sec grab from a longer conversation some of the nuance can be missed so I really wanted to just post a bit more about that here. First of all I want to clarify that while I mention in this grab that women's tendency to worry about a whole lot of things is biological, that isn't the WHOLE story. As I have written in several of my books, gender is more fluid than fixed, and while respecting biological, neurological and hormonal differences, there is not an ‚Äòall men‚Äô or ‚Äòall women‚Äô reality. ON TOP OF THAT, there is social conditioning that is deeply embedded in culture and ancestry. Women are socially conditioned to take care of others and be people pleasers, as I write in my book Girlhood. Just as men are conditioned to be protectors and the strong, silent types. It's not about blaming and shaming each other -- as this story on The Project illustrates well, this conditioning creates a lot of silent expectations on mums and dads, so it can cause conflict. Hopefully having these conversations is about creating greater understanding of what might be at play here so we can then challenge it and parent together better. Thanks to those who have messaged telling us about some great conversations happening and plans to ease the mental load of many mammas. Also, I know that many dads worry about their kids - of course they do! Statistics indicate though that women are more prone to anxious thinking than men. Some research has shown, too, that women are more likely to ruminate than men. And, what I was pointing out to Kate in the Nova interview was not to say that women love their kids more than men. Or that worry makes a better parent... This is just a dynamic that commonly plays out in a lot of heterosexual relationships. And it can create conflict, which could be resolved with honest, real conversations. This chat has obviously struck a chord about potential challenges for those practising ‚Äòteam parenting' and that's a good thing! Exploring how to be the dad you want to be - especially if you had an old school dad - is certainly something some of the dads I've interviewed for the LiSTNR podcast, The Good Enough Dad, have been talking about. And I look forward to hearing more from them to keep this conversation going.

‚ñ™Ô∏èAlmost everyone (including many libertarians) approaches the Israeli/Palestinian conflict wrong. They view it as a disagreement over tribal, collective ‚Äúrights‚Äù to the land. The Jews have historical claim, Palestinian land was stolen, blah blah. There is no such thing as collective, tribal rights to land, that thinking is what has led to most wars throughout history. There‚Äôs only a right to the land particular individuals own, or have cultivated. ‚ñ™Ô∏èVery few Palestinians living today have any legitimate property rights claim to land in Israel. More importantly, that‚Äôs not what they‚Äôre fighting for. #FreePalestine is not a movement to protect the individual rights of Palestinians (or anyone), it‚Äôs a movement to install a dictatorship, a theocracy that controls ‚ÄúPalestinian land.‚Äù Not only is there no right for such a dictatorship to exist, any movement which seeks to implement one is not in any way associated with freedom. ‚ñ™Ô∏èEvery single time Palestinians have been given autonomy and the ability to self rule they have chosen dictatorships and authoritarianism. There are no rights of any kind in Gaza. No freedom of speech, religion, or property rights. If they controlled more land, it would mean more oppression, not only for Israelis but for Palestinians. ‚ñ™Ô∏èIsrael, meanwhile, is a crappy government like the US is a crappy government. It does all sorts of awful things, but it protects basic freedoms. You can be gay in Israel, be a Muslim, be an entrepreneur, be critical of the govt, etc. You can pursue your dreams for the most part. In fact, Arabs living in Israel are far freer (and better off) than those in Gaza or most anywhere else in the Middle East. ‚ñ™Ô∏èNo state who violates any of the rights of its citizens deserves to exist, but in reality this only applies if the alternative is more freedom. Freedom movements are only moral or justified if they call for and actually bring more freedom to an area. The Palestinian cause does not, it only brings tribal rule with a genocidal desire to erase Israel. ‚ñ™Ô∏èIt doesn‚Äôt matter what the historical claims of the Jewish or Palestinian people are (although the Jews have a better claim even there imo). It matters what government is better at protecting its citizens‚Äô rights. In that regard, it‚Äôs not even close in who to support. It‚Äôs night and day morally. It takes brainwashing or a college degree to rationalize supporting ‚ÄúPalestinian freedom‚Äù in the current context.

Our dialogue aimed to address the current war situation and express solidarity and support for the Palestinian people. I conveyed the heartfelt concerns and prayers of the Indian populace to Sheikh Muhammad Hussain, reflecting the deep empathy and understanding of Indian society towards the issues faced by Palestinians on the global stage. In a reciprocal spirit, Sheikh Muhammad Hussain acknowledged the empathetic stance of the Indian people, characterizing them as the society that most genuinely comprehends the Palestinian predicament and their rights at an international level. I highlighted the prayer meetings and solidarity rallies organized by the All India Jamiatul Ulama. I conveyed trying to bring it to the attention of Indian Prime Minister Narendra Modi. How to strengthen your loving relationship...‚úç Everyone‚Äôs relationship is unique, and people come together for many different reasons. But there are some things that good relationships have in common. Knowing the basic principles of healthy relationships helps keep them meaningful, fulfilling and exciting in both happy times and sad: So what makes a healthy love relationship? 1. Staying involved with each other... Some relationships get stuck in peaceful coexistence, but without truly relating to each other and working together. While it may seem stable on the surface, lack of involvement and communication increases distance. When you need to talk about something important, the connection and understanding may no longer be there. 2. Getting through conflict... Some couples talk things out quietly, while others may raise their voices and passionately disagree. The key in a strong relationship, though, is not to be fearful of conflict. You need to be safe to express things that bother you without fear of retaliation, and be able to resolve conflict without humiliation, degradation or insisting on being right. 3. Keeping outside relationships and interests alive... No one person can meet all of our needs, and expecting too much from someone can put a lot of unhealthy pressure on a relationship. Having friends and outside interests not only strengthens your social network, but brings new insights and stimulation to the relationship, too. 4. Communicating... Honest, direct communication is a key part of any relationship. When both people feel comfortable expressing their needs, fears, and desires, trust and bonds are strengthened. Nonverbal cues‚Äîbody language like eye contact, leaning forward or away, or touching someone‚Äôs arm‚Äîare critical to communication.

The Council of Nicaea, also known as the First Council of Nicaea, was a major event in early Christian history. It took place in 325 AD in the city of Nicaea, which is now known as Iznik in modern-day Turkey. The council was convened by the Roman Emperor Constantine I, who sought to resolve a theological dispute that was causing division within the Christian Church. The problem that led to the Council of Nicaea was primarily centered around the teachings of two influential figures: Arius and Alexander of Alexandria. Arius was a presbyter (priest) from Alexandria, Egypt, who challenged the accepted Christian doctrine regarding the nature of Jesus Christ. He believed that Jesus was a created being, separate and subordinate to God the Father. This idea came to be known as Arianism. On the other hand, Alexander, the bishop of Alexandria, held the orthodox belief that Jesus was of the same substance (homoousios) as God the Father, fully divine and co-eternal. He saw Arius' teachings as heretical and a threat to the unity of the Church. The controversy sparked by Arius' teachings ended up dividing the Christian community, causing a significant rupture within the Church. Recognizing the gravity of the situation, Emperor Constantine summoned the Council of Nicaea to address the dispute and bring unity back to the Church. Roughly 250 to 300 bishops attended the council, and they engaged in intense theological debates over the nature of Jesus. After several weeks of discussions and arguments, the council ultimately voted in favor of Alexander's position, refuting Arius' teachings. They formulated what is known as the Nicene Creed, which established the orthodox belief that Jesus is of the same substance as God the Father (homoousios) and declared Arianism as heretical. The council's decision had far-reaching implications. It not only resolved the immediate conflict between Arius and Alexander but also established a foundation for the future theological development of Christianity. The Nicene Creed became a crucial statement of belief for the Church, and its teachings on the divinity of Jesus continue to form an essential part of Christian theology today. The Council of Nicaea is significant not only for its theological outcomes but also for its historical impact. It represents a key moment in the relationship between the Christian Church and the Roman Empire, as it marked the first time a Roman emperor called for and presided over a council of bishops. It also laid the groundwork for subsequent ecumenical councils, which played a critical role in shaping Christian doctrine and resolving doctrinal disputes throughout history. Keep in mind that the Council of Nicaea took place prior to the composition of the New Testament.

It was a couple of years ago now that members of the Animals Australia team met ÿ≥ŸÑÿßŸÑÿ© - Sulala Animal Rescue Founder and Director Saeed, and recognised in him extraordinary courage, commitment, and compassion for animals despite living in one of the most challenging circumstances in Gaza. As a result, we support Sulala‚Äôs efforts for animals through our Emergency Grants Program. When we usually meet with Saeed, it‚Äôs to hear updates about rescues his team has attended, animal welfare training for local community groups or how individual animals have been recovering from treatment. This week though, contact has been fleeting, worried messages as the news of war broke last weekend. We have been trying to get a daily understanding of what it means for him, his family and the many hundreds of animals in his care on the ground in Gaza. Saeed has been remarkably calm as this unimaginable situation unfolds and his concerns are focused on his community of animals and people around him. This is typical of the Saeed we know. We need to be honest and tell you that we don‚Äôt know what is going to happen tomorrow, or in the coming days and weeks for Saeed and the animals. Nobody does. Right now, we know that he and his family achieved an extraordinary feat and managed to move all the cats and dogs out of the evacuation zone where they were living. As a result, the hundreds of animals in Sulala‚Äôs care are still safe and cared for. Our ongoing emergency grant has helped purchase food for the animals, but this supply is limited. Each day we have been sending Saeed messages conveying how much the Animals Australia team, our donors, and this incredible community care about him and his selfless compassion. Communication is difficult because the power and internet access in Gaza has been cut for days now. But he is grateful and feeling supported from afar from a community united by kindness. There are so many unknowns as to what will unfold in coming days and so much that is beyond Saeed‚Äôs control. But we will be standing by, continuing to support Sulala, and the animals in their care, in whatever way we can as the situation becomes clearer. If you would like to donate, please be assured that your generosity will be directed to our response in Gaza: https://animalsaus.co/46S5geR:=:https://animalsaustralia.org/appeal/donate-to-emergency-grants-for-gaza/ We promise we will do everything within our power to help them. Thank you for bearing witness, and for continuing to hold the animals, and all those impacted by this terrible conflict in your hearts. üß°

With GTNP's grizzly #610's recent hit-and-run encounter still front of mind, we'd like to take the opportunity to give a shout-out to our wildlife ambassadors on Togwotee Pass, which has its own roadside grizzlies and where our ambassadors work to keep these animals from becoming too comfortable with people and vehicles. Getting habituated to humans can make bears more comfortable exploring campgrounds and other developed areas. If bears get into human-related foods in those areas, wildlife managers are much more likely to relocate or kill grizzlies to prevent conflict. And of course getting habituated to cars is also a problem--vehicle strikes are a common cause of bear deaths. Whether along a road or in the backcountry, please stay at least 100 yards (about 100 paces) from bears. Elder's Meditation of the Day October 17

"Peace... comes within the souls of men when they realize their relationship, their oneness, with the universe and all its powers, and when they realize that at the center of the Universe dwells Wakan-Tanka, and that this center is really everywhere, it is within each of us."
--Black Elk (Hehaka Sapa) OGLALA SIOUX 

If we are to know peace we must look within ourselves. In order to do this, we must learn to be still. We must quiet the mind. We must learn to meditate. Meditation helps us locate and find the center that is within ourselves. The center is where the Great One resides. When we start to look for peace, we need to realize where it is within ourselves. When we experience conflict we need to pause for a moment and ask the Power within ourselves, "How do you want me to handle this? What would you suggest I do in this situation?" By asking the Higher Power for help we find peace.

Pannun, who lives in Canada, was named as a wanted terrorist in 2020. He is facing more than 20 criminal counts in Punjab. He has threatened Prime Minister Modi, Union Home Minister Amit Shah, and External Affairs Minister Dr S Jaishankar on numerous occasions. SPEECH BY HIS EXCELLENCY, BARRISTER CALEB MANASSEH MUTFWANG, EXECUTIVE GOVERNOR, PLATEAU STATE, DELIVERED AT THE UNITED STATE‚ÄôS INSTITUTE OF PEACE (USIP), WASHINGTON D.C.

FOCUS: Reflections on Plateau State‚Äôs Current State of Play & Forward-Looking Perspectives

Date: 16th October 2023
Venue: United States Institute of Peace (USIP) office, Washington D.C.

Distinguished invited guests and participants physically here seated and those joining us virtually, online.

I bring you warm greetings from the good and peace-loving people of my dear state, Plateau, ‚ÄúThe home of Peace and Tourism‚Äù, which is one of 36 the Federating States in Nigeria üá≥üá¨. I am deeply honoured to deliver a few thoughts on the topic : ‚Äúreflection on Plateau State‚Äôs current state of play & forward-looking perspectives‚Äù while assessing the impact of Nigeria‚Äôs democratic transition on state and local stakeholders.
2. I want to express sincere appreciation to the United States Institute for Peace (USIP) for giving me this opportunity to deliver this reflection on Plateau state, Nigeria, a state I am privileged to lead as Governor.
3. The relationship between Plateau State and the United States Institute of Peace dates to 2014 USIP support for the Yelwa Shendam peace Process that addressed the challenges faced by locals in the community.
Plateau is perhaps the first state to receive USIP support for her Peace Building Agency, which provided funds for from take off till it mature enough to undertake its core mandate of undertaking peace initiatives.
Let me also state that Plateau is also a beneficiary of the Network of Nigerian Facilitators (NNF) Programme implemented by USIP. The support provided to the NNF to work in Mangu local government on peace mediation is also being replicated in the Ganawuri- Manchok areas in Plateau State. USIP‚Äôs model in supporting local partners is key towards sustainability of impactful initiatives.
4. Plateau State is the twelfth-largest Nigerian state. It‚Äôs located near the capital of Nigeria and includes a range of hills surrounding the Jos Plateau, its capital, and the entire plateau itself. Plateau State is described as "The Home of Peace and Tourism" due to its natural formations of rocks, hills and waterfalls. It derives its name from the Jos Plateau. Plateau State is strategically located in the North Central part of Nigeria. The state is greatly endowed economically, by virtue of its rich agriculture, solid minerals, power potentials and tourism with vast land.

Although situated in the tropical zone, the higher altitude gives the state a near-temperate climate, with an average temperature between 13 and 22 ¬∞C.
Known for its heterogeneity, the state has about 54 autochthonous ethnic groups, among which are the Tarok, Ankwei, Angas, Jarawa, Berom, Mwaghavul, among others. The mining industry attracted Europeans and other foreign nationals, while trade and other geographical advantages drew Igbo (Ibo), Hausa and Yoruba immigrants into the state.

5. It is pertinent to state that Plateau State is a reflection of the diversity of Nigeria with different ethnic groups, different faiths, but who have all historically lived peacefully with each other. These people naturally don‚Äôt fight each other. 

Although the media is filled with n erroneous narrative of farmers-Herders / Indigenes- Settler‚Äôs clash, I make bold to say that there is no violent and disruptive conflict between herders and farmers in Plateau State. This narrative has been imposed by the media and persons who want to sound politically correct.

While it is true that there have been skirmishes between farmers and herders, they have traditionally coexisted symbiotically. These skirmishes are usually settled using traditional dispute mechanisms. Truth be told, what we have today are the violent activities of terrorists and bandits, carrying offensive military-type weapons, ravaging rural Plateau, killing and sacking the local populations, and taking over the land. Today, dozens of communities in Riyom, Barkin Ladi, Mangu, Bokkos LGAs have been sacked by the bandits and taken over by armed grazing marauders. These cannot be referred to as conflict between farmers and herders.

6. It will interest you to know that the Plateau conflict is not isolated. It is replicated in key states of the Middle Belt: Nasarawa, Benue, Taraba, the FCT, Niger, Kaduna, and the Northwestern states of Katsina, Kebbi, Sokoto and Zamfara.

It is also worth noting that the suspected instigators and beneficiaries of these conflicts have often given the crises a religious colouration since the 1990s, however, religion has only been used as a convenient survival strategy for political advantage and economic dominance.

7. The 2001 crisis was the single largest violent conflict that happened within the city of Jos in which over 1000 persons were killed. This upset and reconfigured Jos the capital city. It is gratifying to note that with some measures taken in recent (truncated)

text: US Secretary of State Antony Blinken announced Biden‚Äôs travel to Israel as the humanitarian situation in the Gaza Strip grows more dire and as Israel prepares for a possible ground attack on the 141-square-mile (365-square-kilometer) territory to root out Hamas militants responsible for what US and Israeli officials say was the most lethal assault against Jews since the Holocaust. But Biden‚Äôs presence could be seen as a provocative move by Hamas‚Äô chief sponsor, Iran, or potentially viewed as tone-deaf by Arab nations as civilian casualties mount in Gaza. Blinken has already been traveling around the Mideast this past week trying to prevent the war with Hamas from igniting a broader regional conflict. Blinken made the announcement early Tuesday after more than seven hours of talks with Israeli Prime Minister Benjamin Netanyahu and other top Israeli officials. ‚ÄúHe is coming here at a critical moment for Israel, for the region and for the world,‚Äù Blinken said. Shortly after in Washington, White House National Security Council spokesman John Kirby announced that Biden would also go to Jordan to meet with King Abdullah II, Egyptian President Abdel Fattah el-Sissi and Palestinian President Mahmoud Abbas. White House officials said Biden‚Äôs talks with Arab leaders in Amman will largely focus on humanitarian concerns for Gaza‚Äôs 2.3 million people. He‚Äôll also make clear that Hamas does not stand for the Palestinian people‚Äôs right to dignity and self-determination. ‚ÄúWe are not putting conditions on the military assistance that we are providing to Israel,‚Äù Kirby said. ‚ÄúThey have a right to defend themselves. They have a right to go after this terrorist threat.‚Äù | via Associated Press

My heart has been heavy and my thoughts have been with the people of Palestine. A land rich in history, steeped in faith, and resilient in the face of adversity. A land that has endured the winds of conflict and the storms of occupation for far too long. This isn't about politics or religion, but about humanity. Regardless of where we come from or what we believe in, we must all stand for justice, for peace, and for the sanctity of human life. The people of Palestine are more than just headlines or statistics. They are mothers and fathers, daughters and sons, dreamers and doers, who deserve to live in dignity, freedom, and peace. They deserve a future where fear does not shadow their every step, where the night brings dreams, not dread, and where their rights as a human are respected and protected. It's time for us to use our voices to shine a light on the ongoing plight of Palestinians. To speak out against the injustices they face daily. To advocate for their right to self-determination. To pray for an end to their suffering. As we scroll through our feeds from the comfort of our homes, let's remember those who are living amidst the rubble, those whose lives hang in the balance, and those whose stories of courage and perseverance inspire us. May we never lose sight of our shared humanity. May we stand in solidarity with the oppressed, no matter where they are. And may our prayers and actions contribute to a future where peace and justice reign in Palestine. #PrayForPalestine üïäÔ∏èüôè

Stu Burguiere breaks down the media's coverage shift on the recent Israel-Hamas conflict in Gaza, from initial sympathy for Israeli victims to increased criticism of Israel's military response. He questions why the media isn't focusing more on American hostages being held in Gaza by Hamas. Stu argues Israel's past decision to withdraw from Gaza empowered Hamas terrorists, asserting Israel now needs to reclaim control of the region. He shows examples of large pro-Palestinian protests in America and discusses the complexities around public figures taking a stance. Stu criticizes celebrities and the "Me Too" movement for not unambiguously condemning Hamas's horrific crimes like rape and murder of civilians. He argues for clear moral clarity against Hamas terrorism in this conflict.

This year, Delegates of the Historical Crisis Council (HCC) will be presented with the opportunity to reexamine and relive one of the most infamous wars on North American soil in the 19th century ‚Äì the Mexican‚ÄìAmerican War. Topic: Mexican‚ÄìAmerican War Both Mexico and the United States had their own set of issues by the time the conflict broke out. The former had been suffering from constant instability during its first three decades and a half of independence from the Spanish Empire. The latter, while an ever-expanding force of power, saw internal divisions from race and inequality grow greater and greater. Tensions over the independence of California and the incorporation of Texas into the US directly exacerbated disputes and led to the American invasion of its southern neighbors in 1846. The subsequent two-year conflict was one of the major precursors to the most divisive conflict in American history - the Civil War. At HMUN Mock #18, Delegates will play the role of prominent political and military figures on either side of the conflict, with the aim of not only achieving victory in battles but also securing territory and stability for their nation. Delegates will have to work closely with one another, noting their differences, to construct strategic successes and internal harmony. Which nation shall emerge victorious from these battles? Will there be long-lasting peace, or will division be here to stay? text: Good afternoon folks. I've been given the latitude to make a post here today as to the basic structure of the Justice for K9 Officer Chase page that we'd like not to vary from. Recently it's been brought to my attention that there's been a lot of internal friction between folks and derogatory comments made about other folks that belong to the group, and there's been some deliberately confrontational statements made amongst some of the members. I want to bring a few things to light if I may. One of them is we have a new group coming on board with us that has shown support and compassion for our efforts to bring Chase home. I certainly don't want these folks to be reading posts that have to do with a lot of internal conflict because I think quite frankly that will just make them go a different direction rather than supporting us and we don't want that to happen. I've also noticed and have been taking notice over the past month or so that there has just been a lot of speculation on people's part as to what happened and there's been a lot of specific statements made that cannot be validated or proven. I'm also seeing a lot of verbal bashing of particular individuals without us even really knowing all the pertinent information that needs to be had before making any statements of such. I personally think that statements like"Chase is dead and he's never coming back"and other statements like"he was thrown into the river or he died in a hot car"which nobody can prove need to come to an end. If you make a statement that is deliberately non-factual your post will be removed and you will be cautioned. If you make a statement such as"if Chase is at the rainbow bridge God bless him"certainly is compassionate and not viewed as derogatory. We need to get back to the initial focus of this page and that is to provide positive information and support to the members on this page that try to bring compassion and hope to the page for other folks who have the same feelings. The bashing and the name calling and the confrontational statements and the deliberately hurtful statements and information that is not factual will not be tolerated. You are free to speculate in your own mind as to what you think has happened or has not happened. We would like to keep this page up and running, and I can't imagine how many people have just walked away seeing the internal strife along with arguments and the friction between people with their posts and insinuations. Could we please revert back to the initial focus and plan that we had put in place months ago when this page was started and that is just one focus, and one focus only. That is to bring Chase home. I get a lot of private messages from people telling me they don't like what they see or what they have read that is negative and confrontational in content. That absolutely needs to stop today without exception without argument. I've never been one to be extremely eloquent with my conversation and have been pretty much right to the point with what I've had to say, however at this point I thought using the discretion to be as diplomatic as possible would be in order. Please, please do not make us ban people from the page because they're focus is totally different and accusatory which leads to arguments and conflicts. Please do not do that anymore. This page has always been about Chase and bringing Chase home and quite frankly there's not one of us that can do anything about the situation with Mr. Dudley and or his sentencing or his punishment. You never know who's trolling this page and we certainly don't want to look like a bunch of unprofessional, accusatory vigilantes so to speak. Let's get back to being professional and bringing compassion and positive thoughts to the page. Thank you for your time and consideration. One last thing, because this is my post this is my choice for picture.

Proud of you Meira Paibi Sons ‚ù§Ô∏è‚ù§Ô∏è‚ù§Ô∏è‚ù§Ô∏èüôèüáÆüá≥ Romi Meitei, Saikhom Ratan shine at 69th National Film Awards, Delhi DIPR Imphal: Amid turbulent times besetting Manipur, two critical filmmakers from the state ‚Äì Mayanglangbam Romi Meitei and Saikhom Ratan - on Tuesday bagged awards at the 69th edition of National Film Awards, New Delhi. Besides the two, acclaimed filmmaker, Borun Thokcom, also from the state, was a proud spectator at the glittering awards ceremony as he was among a few film personalities of the nation who were jury members of non-feature film category. President Draupadi Murmu conferred the awards to the outstanding filmmakers and cast and crews at the ceremony attended by a constellation of great Indian movie stars and promoters. This year, the ‚ÄúDada Saheb Phalke Award‚Äù (lifetime achievement award), the highest film honour of the country, went to yester year‚Äôs shinning bollywood beauty, Waheda Raham. President Murmu, praised Waham and said she represents a women of substance and a shining symbol of an empowered woman. Romi received the award for his iconic feature film ‚ÄúEikhoigi Yum‚Äù (Our house), while Ratan went home with the award for his flick ‚ÄúBeyond Blast‚Äù. Romi was honoured with the best Manipuri feature film category, while Ratan bagged the best biographical non feature film award. Before making a debut with parallel cinema with ‚ÄúEikhoigi Yum‚Äù, Romi was an successful mainstream commercial filmmaker as he made over 100 such movies most of which were box office hits. Minutes after bagging his first ever National film award Romi DIPR that Tuesday‚Äôs event was great and memorial, but the current crisis gripping the state has dampened his celebratory moods. ‚ÄúI‚Äôm very happy with the recognition given to ‚ÄúEikhoigi Yum‚Äù which is my first non-commercial project. As much as I wished, I‚Äôm unable to enjoy the moment considering the conflict going on in Manipur,‚Äù Romi quipped. ‚ÄúI must thank Manipur State Film Development Society (MFSDS) for the inspiration it has provided me with the yearlong events it organized to commemorate the Golden Jubilee of Manipuri Cinema (1972-2022). In fact, ‚ÄúEikhoigi Yum‚Äù had the privilege of opening one of the highlights of the celebration, the first ‚ÄòEikhoigi Imphal International Film Festival‚Äô (EIIFF),‚Äù he said. Ratan said Tuesday‚Äôs awards ceremony ‚Äúis the pinnacle of my filmmaking journey which started in 1992. I‚Äôm overwhelmed by this honour. But sadly, the situation back home prevents me to indulge.‚Äù Jury member Borun who is himself a national awardee filmmaker officiated as jury member for the national honours for the first time said ‚Äúwe had to view more than 200 short and documentary films in multi-languages. However, at the end of the day, beauty has no language barriers and language of cinema presided, and films made with passion and with the right intent stood out as always. I feel happy that Manipuri filmmakers did well in both the categories, feature and non-feature.

During the American Civil War, Virginia resident William Terrill Bradby was one of an estimated 20,000 Native Americans who served with Union military forces in the fight against the Confederacy. A large part of Bradby‚Äôs own contributions to the Union cause involved maritime transportation. A member of the Pamunkey Tribe, Bradby was born in Virginia in 1833. After the Civil War broke out in 1861, Bradby remained loyal to the Union even though Virginia joined the Confederacy. Bradby‚Äôs unwavering decision to side with the North resulted in his church expelling him from its congregation. Even more significantly, his military service on behalf of the Union often placed him at high risk and in harm‚Äôs way. Bradby‚Äôs initial activities with the Union forces included serving as a land guide and scout for the Army of the Potomac during the Peninsula Campaign in southeastern Virginia in 1862. The following year, however, Bradby exchanged those land-based assignments for ‚Äúwater duty‚Äù when he joined the Union Navy. Throughout the remainder of the war, Bradby served on a variety of military ships and boats and even piloted several of those vessels. For a good part of 1863-64, for example, he was a pilot second class for vessels that were part of a Union flotilla on the James River in Virginia. While serving on the steamship USS Shokokon on that river, Bradby was shot in the leg by a Confederate shell. This injury turned out to be only a flesh wound, but it brought about rheumatism that would plague Bradby for the remainder of his days. Other vessels on which Bradby served were the gunboats USS Onondaga and USS Huron; the tugboat USS Epsilon; the steamship USS Daylight; and the torpedo boat USS Spuyten Duyvil. There were several other Native Americans from Virginia who likewise served the Union as guides and pilots during the war. They included Bradby‚Äôs brother Sterling as well as Thornton Allmond, John Langston, William Sampson, and Powhatan Weisiger. William Terrill Bradby‚Äôs own military record, however, is one of the most detailed and best documented of that group. After the Civil War ended, Bradby returned to where he had lived prior to the conflict: the Pamunkey reservation on the western shore of the Chesapeake Bay in Virginia. Bradby remained there for the rest of his life, becoming one the most respected members of the community. He died sometime around 1905.

Official Statement on the Vote for Speaker of the House This week, when members of the House of Representatives reconvene to vote for a speaker, they will have the opportunity to demonstrate their enduring commitment to our Constitutional system of government. While a handful of extremists have precipitated a crisis of leadership, an equally small number of courageous and reasonable actors have the opportunity to exhibit bipartisanship and restore faith in ethical governance. As leaders and members of Mormon Women for Ethical Government, we ask all members of Congress, regardless of party affiliation, to find a pathway to the election of a speaker who has proven they will support the peaceful transfer of power. We are once again faced with a conflict within our governing bodies that would have previously seemed unthinkable. As citizens, we are asked to accept an impossible compromise ‚Äî tolerate congressional leaders who have worked to undermine a legitimate election, or risk having no functioning government at all. It is important for our elected representatives to see this compromise for what it is ‚Äî an extortionate lie. Installing a speaker who previously voted against the certification of the 2020 election will compromise the security and stability of our nation. Those who worked to undermine the last election should not be trusted to oversee the next one. In the election for House leadership, it falls to members of the majority party to control their extreme factions. Key Republican members of the House must stand fast and work to elect a speaker who has demonstrated respect both for their colleagues and for legislative norms and processes. In addition, we earnestly plead with members of the Democratic caucus to work across the aisle with Republicans who are committed to upholding the rule of law. Any Democrat who votes to elect competent and ethical House leadership could reasonably claim to be a principled defender of good government, national security, fiscal responsibility, and respect for the individual citizens of this nation. These things must matter more than party politics. We are in a moment when it feels as though much of the world is in chaos. Sadly, the chaos we are experiencing at home is being recklessly self-inflicted. It is time for our leaders to make choices that will benefit the nation, and the members of the U.S. House of Representatives can begin this week by choosing to vote in defense of Constitutional government. We ask that they prioritize preservation of the rule of law, protection of national norms, and an absolute and unshakable commitment to the peaceful transfer of power above all other political objectives. The people of our nation deserve no less from their leaders. #officialstatement

Hello my fellow Llanites, I had someone come up to me this past week and try and explain that the correct term for citizens of Llano should be Llanoans. I explained why I refer to the people of the City of Llano as Llanites rather than Llanoans or Llanoians. Llanite is a special form of granite unique in all the world. It is a tough and beautiful rock with properties that set it apart from other forms of granite. It is one-of-a-kind. Llanoians sounds like a type of floor covering. Something to be walked on, unnoticed and common. I like to use the term that more accurately describes the people of our community, special, beautiful, and unique. You may or may not have been aware that this past Saturday was Llano Day at the State Fair of Texas. It was also, unfortunately a day that a shooting took place and three people were injured. For Llano, it represented another case of where an outside source came into our party and injected an element of fear and division. I cannot and will not get into details of what I am specifically referring to at this point in time, however, let me say that outside elements have been driving division and misconception in our community. Read into that whatever you want, but my point is that prior to such outside input, we were a much more cohesive community. I would like to get back to that. I can hear it now, ‚ÄúWhy don't you just say what you mean!‚Äù Believe me, I would love to do exactly that, but the constraints of position and office preclude me from doing so. Suffice it to say that regardless of what wedge of division that is being driven into Llano, we as a community can choose to get along, or not. I would hope that the ties that bind us together are strong enough to endure and outlast such pressures from outside sources. Remember you have more in common with your next-door neighbor than you do with someone from Austin or Washington or anyplace else. Given the current world situation, that is more important than ever. I am writing this early Sunday morning and by the time you read it, the world could have changed radically. I will give you an example. The situation in the middle east is beginning to boil rapidly and you may think that we are well removed from the direct effects of that conflict. That is not the case. I will remind you of our proximity to the border. A number of years ago, Hamas made a coalition with the cartels in Mexico. The cartels have money for weapons, and Hamas has plenty of military weapons and needs money. The cartels also have a well-developed network for smuggling people or products. It was a natural business development. While the latest reports that I have seen show that there is no immediate threat known to the State of Texas, situational awareness is of the utmost importance. I also know of a good number of organizations and institutions that are stepping up their game in being prepared and aware. Larger churches are tightening up their security teams, schools are checking their security measures and briefings are going on in law enforcement agencies. In other words, this is no joke. The US has deployed troops to Northern Gaza, we have a second aircraft carrier headed to the Mediterranean and the world seems to be choosing up sides. We as a community need to get beyond what differences we have and come back together. I am certainly not trying to scare anyone, but I am stating some facts. The world we live in today is very different to the one we inhabited pre-Covid. We as a community need to rise to the occasion rather than sink into the circumstances. The world has become a much more dangerous place, even in just the last couple of weeks. Time to put aside differences and pull together in the harness of our community. I don't want to be preachy or come off sounding sanctimonious, but this is very important and we need to start today. I love Llano, it is without a doubt the best place I have ever lived. Let's not allow outside forces to drive us apart or change us into something we are not. For those who don't know, when you take a piece of Llanite and expose it to the light, there is a beauty and blue sparkle that is almost like a gemstone. I want to you see yourselves as Llanites, special people who are unique, tough but caring, resourceful, and resolute, with a beauty and sparkle that is like that of the Llanite stone. Regardless of what the world throws at us we can excel. In the words of Hank Jr. ‚Äúcountry folks can survive.‚Äù

For those like me who sometimes feel like Dakota County is getting too dense, the conflict in Israel and Gaza provides perspective. Dakota County is four times larger than Gaza and home to 755 people per square mile. The Gaza Strip is nearly 20 times as dense, with a whopping 14,628 residents per square mile. Similarly, Minnesota has 10 times the land as Israel, yet Israel possesses twice the population. This means there are 60 people per square mile living in Minnesota, compared with over 1,000 people per square mile in Israel. While the region's history of conflict and cultural clashes cannot be overstated, it makes me appreciate even more all the elbow room and resources we have available to us here in Dakota County and across Minnesota.

How to strengthen your loving relationship...‚úç Everyone‚Äôs relationship is unique, and people come together for many different reasons. But there are some things that good relationships have in common. Knowing the basic principles of healthy relationships helps keep them meaningful, fulfilling and exciting in both happy times and sad: So what makes a healthy love relationship? 1. Staying involved with each other... Some relationships get stuck in peaceful coexistence, but without truly relating to each other and working together. While it may seem stable on the surface, lack of involvement and communication increases distance. When you need to talk about something important, the connection and understanding may no longer be there. 2. Getting through conflict... Some couples talk things out quietly, while others may raise their voices and passionately disagree. The key in a strong relationship, though, is not to be fearful of conflict. You need to be safe to express things that bother you without fear of retaliation, and be able to resolve conflict without humiliation, degradation or insisting on being right. 3. Keeping outside relationships and interests alive... No one person can meet all of our needs, and expecting too much from someone can put a lot of unhealthy pressure on a relationship. Having friends and outside interests not only strengthens your social network, but brings new insights and stimulation to the relationship, too. 4. Communicating... Honest, direct communication is a key part of any relationship. When both people feel comfortable expressing their needs, fears, and desires, trust and bonds are strengthened. Nonverbal cues‚Äîbody language like eye contact, leaning forward or away, or touching someone‚Äôs arm‚Äîare critical to communication.

How can you tell if your conflicts are really resolved? Here‚Äôs a short acrostic using the word REAL that you can use as a checklist to make sure your conflicts are actually being resolved: R - Do you completely RECEIVE your spouse despite the conflict? Receiving each other is the foundation of REAL resolution. Although unresolved conflict causes at least some division, receiving your spouse before, during, and after the conflict minimizes the gap. Receiving your spouse despite a conflict tells them that they are more important than the resolution. E - Did both of you EXPRESS yourselves authentically? Conflict requires mutual understanding of each other‚Äôs perspective. Mutual understanding requires both of you to speak the truth in love about how you feel about the topic. If there‚Äôs something less than truth being spoken on one or both sides, the conflict is likely not resolved and will probably come up again. A - Did both of you ADMIT your fault? Talking through a conflict or issue will typically reveal areas that need to be confessed by both of you. REAL Resolution isn‚Äôt just being willing to confess, but searching for opportunities to confess to each other for how you contributed towards the issue‚Ä¶regardless of who is more at fault. L - Can you both express what you LEARNED about yourselves and each other in response to the conflict? When you experience REAL resolution, you should walk away knowing yourself and each other better so you can respond differently to similar situations moving forward. . . . #realresolution #conflict #conflictresolution #marriage #marriagerevolution #resolution #fightfair

Helen Mitchell (getrouwd met Colin die op het Vrij Zijn Weekend in februari hoopt te spreken) beschrijft een indrukwekkende ervaring op haar blog. Colin en Helen hebben twee Palestijnse kinderen geadopteerd. Colin is nog steeds in Haifa Isra√´l: Toen ons vliegtuig zaterdagavond opsteeg - een gecharterde vlucht georganiseerd door de Britse regering om haar burgers te redden van de oorlog in Isra√´l - brak ik in tranen uit. Voor het eerst sinds het begin van de oorlog gunde ik mezelf de luxe om te huilen - diepe, zware snikken uit de bodem van mijn longen. Ik probeerde de tranen niet langer te bedwingen, zoals ik de hele week had gedaan, voor het geval ze de kinderen zouden waarschuwen voor de ernst van de situatie, of voor het geval de diepte van mijn verdriet me zou verhinderen helder te denken en snel te handelen. Terwijl we hoog boven de flikkerende lichten van wegen, auto's en huizen uitstegen, werd ik overmand door verdriet om het lijden van de mensen in dit prachtige land. Ik huilde om alle ouders, kinderen, ouderen en jongeren die een week eerder wakker waren geworden met de gedachte dat het een gewone Shabbat zou worden, om zich vervolgens binnen een fractie van een seconde in een van de wreedste bloedbaden te bevinden die de wereld ooit heeft gezien. Omdat ik zelf moeder ben, waren het de verhalen van de kinderen die me verscheurden, en hun ouders die stierven terwijl ze hen probeerden te beschermen, zonder succes. Terwijl ik in het vliegtuig zat, merkte ik dat ik steeds maar weer zei: "Het spijt me, het spijt me". Ik voelde me zo schuldig dat ik nu mijn mensen in Isra√´l achterliet. Dat ik in het vliegtuig zat op weg naar veiligheid, terwijl zovelen van hen nooit de kans hebben gekregen. Dat zoveel families in Isra√´l zich in een hel bevinden met geliefden die gegijzeld worden in Gaza, met zonen en dochters die vechten en sterven aan het front, met raketten en sirenes en chaos en terreur. "Het spijt me zo, Isra√´l, dat ik jullie nu verlaat." Terwijl ik huilde, vroeg mijn zevenjarige dochter die naast me zat niet waarom. Ze begon gewoon stilletjes haar eigen verzonnen liedje te zingen. "Mama, het is goed, je kleine meisje is nu bij je. Je dochter houdt van je en je hoeft geen pijn te hebben." Dit was het kleine meisje dat een paar uur eerder nog in paniek had gegild omdat ze zo bang was voor de oorlog, het kleine meisje dat ik niet goed had kunnen vasthouden of troosten omdat ik zo wanhopig was om ons op de vlucht te krijgen. Later, toen we in Engeland aankwamen en ik ontdooid was, bedankte ik mijn dochter voor haar vliegtuigliedje. Ik sloeg mijn armen om haar heen en hield haar stevig vast tot ze zich weer veilig voelde. Maar ik zou ook denken aan die andere moeders in het zuiden van Isra√´l die geen macht hadden om hun kinderen veilig te houden, hoe stevig ze hen ook vasthielden. Vanochtend nog las ik een verslag over de forensische pathologen die bezig waren om de menselijke resten van het bloedbad te identificeren. Ze stuitten op een vorm die zo misvormd was dat ze pas na een CT-scan beseften dat het om twee afzonderlijke lichamen ging: een volwassene en een kind die elkaar stevig omhelsden terwijl ze verbrandden. Geliefd Isra√´l, mijn hart breekt voor jullie. Ik heb een zee van tranen. Maar tegelijkertijd voelen mijn tranen als een luxe waar ik geen recht op heb, want hier ben ik, veilig weg van het conflict, in staat om mijn twee gezonde kinderen te knuffelen en hen te laten weten dat ze veilig zijn. Ik heb geen theologie, geen wijsheid, geen verklaringen voor wat er is gebeurd. Misschien wel nooit. Ik voel geen behoefte of druk om er iets zinnigs over te zeggen. Ik wil God niet vragen waarom. Misschien weet ik dat als ik dat doe, ik alleen maar boos zal worden. Maar zonder te proberen iets te begrijpen, voel ik een diep gevoel van Gods aanwezigheid. Dat Hij op de een of andere manier in de duisternis mijn hand vasthoudt. En dat Hij ook huilt.

üéÇOn October 17, 1948 the late actress Margot Kidder was born in Yellowknife, Northwest Territories, Canada. She began her acting career in the 1960s, appearing in low-budget Canadian films and television series, before landing a lead role in Quackser Fortune Has a Cousin in the Bronx (1970). She then played twins in Brian De Palma's psychological horror thriller Sisters (1973), a sorority student in the slasher film Black Christmas (1974) and the titular character's girlfriend in the drama The Great Waldo Pepper (1975), opposite Robert Redford. In 1977, she was cast as Lois Lane in Richard Donner's Superman (1978), a role that established her as a mainstream actress. Her performance as Kathy Lutz in the blockbuster horror film The Amityville Horror (1979) gained her further mainstream exposure, after which she went on to reprise her role as Lois Lane in Superman II (1980), Superman III (1983), and Superman IV: The Quest for Peace (1987). text: 8 key lessons to learn from "Emotional Intelligence" by Daniel Goleman. 1. UNDERSTANDING EMOTIONAL INTELLIGENCE (EI): You will learn that Emotional Intelligence (EI) is not just about being 'book smart.' It involves understanding and managing emotions effectively, both in yourself and in others. 2. FIVE COMPONENTS OF EMOTIONAL INTELLIGENCE: a. Self-Awareness: : You'll realize the importance of recognizing and understanding your own emotions and how they influence your actions and decisions. b. Self-Regulation: You'll discover the necessity of controlling and managing your emotions in various situations to achieve the outcomes you desire. c. Motivation: You'll understand the power of channeling your emotions towards achieving your personal and professional goals, often requiring perseverance and resilience. d. Empathy: You'll grasp the significance of understanding and sharing the feelings of others, which can help you build better relationships and communicate effectively. e. Social skills: You'll acknowledge the value of navigating social interactions effectively, including communication, conflict resolution, and building rapport. 3. THE BRAIN AND EMOTIONAL INTELLIGENCE: You'll gain insights into how the brain's structure and functions are interconnected with emotional responses and behaviors, helping you understand how emotions impact your thought processes and decision-making. 4. THE ROLE OF CHILDHOOD AND PARENTING: You'll learn how early experiences and parental influence significantly shape a child's emotional development, laying the foundation for their emotional intelligence in adulthood. 5. THE POWER OF EMOTIONAL COMPETENCE IN LEADERSHIP: You'll understand the significance of EI for effective leadership, realizing that great leaders possess strong emotional intelligence, enabling them to understand, motivate, and lead their teams more effectively. 6. MANAGING RELATIONSHIPS AND SOCIAL AWARENESS: You'll recognize the importance of gaining proficiency in managing relationships and being socially aware. It involves empathetic listening, understanding non-verbal cues, and fostering positive relationships. 7. EMOTIONAL INTELLIGENCE IN THE WORKPLACE: You'll realize how EI can influence your professional success, including areas like teamwork, negotiation, conflict resolution, and leadership. You'll understand that developing high EI can make you more successful and influential in your career. 8. CULTIVATING EMOTIONAL INTELLIGENCE: You'll become aware of the need to enhance your emotional intelligence through self-reflection, mindfulness, emotional regulation exercises, and continuous learning. You'll understand that EI is a skill that can be developed and improved over time. Book: https://amzn.to/3Q2tFaO:=:https://www.amazon.com/emotional-intelligence-daniel-goleman-book/s?k=emotional+intelligence+daniel+goleman+book

Kaunseling adalah asas kesejahteraan mental dan emosi. Sesi kaunseling yang menyediakan ruang yang selesa dan selamat bagi seseorang individu untuk meluahkan perasaan, mendapatkan bimbingan serta sokongan emosi. Ia merupakan persekitaran yang tidak menghakimi bagi mereka dalam berkongsi keresahan, meringankan bebanan serta menggalakkan pembentukan jati diri. Selain itu, kaunseling ini juga akan memupuk hubungan yang lebih sihat dalam meningkatkan kemahiran berkomunikasi dan penyelesaian konflik, ia juga boleh mengukuhkan hubungan bersama orang yang terpenting. Pada dasarnya, kaunseling menyokong kesihatan mental, pertumbuhan keperibadian, dan ketahanan daya tahan diri, memperkasakan individu untuk mengharungi cabaran hidup dan memupuk kesejahteraan emosi. Bagi mereka yang ingin menjalani kehidupan yang lebih baik, kami menjemput anda untuk sertai dan mengambil peluang ini untuk sesi percuma bersama Kaunselor Pelatih dalaman NUBE - Cik Vanyza Sarveswaran. ***************************** Counselling is a cornerstone of mental and emotional well-being. It provides a safe space for individuals to express themselves, seek guidance, and find emotional support. It is a non-judgmental environment to share concerns, alleviate distress, and promote self-discovery. Additionally, counselling nurtures healthier relationships by enhancing communication and conflict resolution skills, strengthening connections with the ones that matter. In essence, counselling supports mental health, personal growth, and resilience, empowering individuals to navigate life's challenges and fostering emotional well-being. For those seeking a more fulfilling life, we invite you to take this opportunity for a free session with NUBE‚Äôs in-house Trainee Counselor - Ms Vanyza Sarveswaran.

See below statement by the PPP on the Israeli-Palestinian Conflict: The People‚Äôs Progressive Party (PPP) has historically stood in support of a two-state solution to resolve the Israeli-Palestinian conflict, in keeping with UN resolution 242. Events of this last week have catapulted this issue onto the forefront of the global agenda once again, and require more urgent, determined, sustained, and unequivocal efforts by the United Nations (UN) and global leaders to realise this resolution. Hamas‚Äô attack on Israeli territory, and the subsequent Israeli aerial bombardment, as well as the consequential cutting off of all access to fuel, electricity, water, and medicine to the people of Gaza, have brought the status of the Israeli-Palestinian conflict to its lowest levels in several decades. Hamas‚Äô attack on Israel has resulted in the loss of over 1,400 lives, including that of women and children. Meanwhile, the Israeli bombardment of Gaza has resulted in the deaths of over 2,600 Palestinians, many of whom are children and women. This violence against innocent civilians, on both sides, is unacceptable and the PPP unequivocally condemns it. Further, the Israeli air raids on Gaza have also resulted in the indiscriminate destruction of essential infrastructure, including UN centers, hospitals, and schools ‚Äì all in flagrant violation of international and humanitarian laws. At this dangerous juncture, there is a real threat that the conflict will escalate and engulf all of Palestine, as well as other parts of the Region. The People‚Äôs Progressive Party lends its unequivocal support to the statement by the Secretary General of the United Nations, Ant√≥nio Guterres, on October 13, 2023, in which he called on Israel to stop the evacuation order of over one million people from the Gaza, one of the most densely populated areas in the world ‚Äì ‚Äúa territory already besieged under aerial bombardment without fuel, electricity, water and food.‚Äù The Secretary-General appealed to Israel to reconsider such actions, as it would have devastating humanitarian consequences. Also, the PPP welcomes the swift response by the Caribbean Community (CARICOM). The October 9, 2023 statement stressed that CARICOM joined ‚Äúresponsible members of the international community in calling for an immediate ceasefire and the end of hostilities by all parties. CARICOM continues to support UNSC Res 242 and the ongoing efforts towards a two-state solution as the best way to achieve comprehensive peace, security and tranquility between Israel and Palestine.‚Äù Additionally, statements by world leaders have urged Israel to withdraw the evacuation order for over a million Palestinians and for it to not reoccupy Gaza as its own. The PPP reiterates that it condemns the senseless killing of innocent civilians, particularly women and children, on both sides and supports the call for: ‚óè The immediate, rapid, and unimpeded humanitarian access throughout Gaza of fuel, food, medicine and water, etc., being allowed to enter; ‚óè An immediate reversal of the evacuation order by Israel of the Palestinians in Gaza; ‚Ä¢ All hostages in Gaza to be released; and ‚óè International humanitarian laws to be respected and upheld, and for civilians on both sides to be protected at all times. The world can no longer continue to turn a blind eye to the unacceptable conditions in which the Palestinians have been living for generations. The Palestinian people deserve a homeland in which they can live in freedom and dignity. The people of Israel also deserve to live in a country free from threats of violence and at peace with their neighbours. We believe that this can only be achieved in the context of a two-state solution.

Residents in the Gaza Strip are still facing severe water shortages after Israel turned water supplies back on in parts of southern #Gaza on Sunday, Oct. 15. Water supplies only lasted for three hours, and only benefits 14 percent of 2.2 million population in Gaza Strip, the UN said on Monday. The UN recognizes that access to #water as a human right. The lack of clean water is putting lives in danger, raising concerns for #dehydration, and spread of #infections like cholera and dysentery, the UN says. Water supplies in the Gaza Strip rely on neighborhood #desalination facilities and public taps, as the region‚Äôs only aquifer is #contaminated by sewage, chemicals, and seawater. Even before the latest Israel-Hamas conflict, 90 percent of the water was undrinkable, according to the Palestinian Water Authority. Some people in the Strip are now desperately searching for drinking water. They are digging wells near the sea and some are consuming water from contaminated sources, Reuters reports. #cgtnamerica

We are not just a BUS museum and we are not just a LORRY museum, we have a number of vehicles from the transport industry under our roof. The history of Transport is important to us and we like to have some unusual vehicles in our collection whether they are owned by us, or by private owners, we think there is something for everyone. How about a huge warship? Yes we have three of them. HMS Vangaurd, HMS Implecable and HMS Sheffield built by one gentleman over many years. We have all seen the Airfix and Revell model kits, but these are a little bit bigger and are situated on our Mezzanine floor with the model railway in the main hall. 'HMS Sheffield was a Type 42 guided missile destroyer and the second Royal Navy ship to be named after the city of Sheffield in Yorkshire. Commissioned on 16 February 1975 the Sheffield was part of the Task Force 317 sent to the Falkland Islands during the Falklands War. Nickname: Shiny Sheff Fate: Sunk on 10 May 1982 (Info - https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/HMS_Sheffield_:=:https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/HMS_Sheffield(D80)) You can see a photo of HMS Sheffield below and you can see HMS Vanguard and HMS Implecable on our Open Day - 12th November 2023 from 10.30am till 4.00pm and we will be having a minute silence at 11.00am on the day to remember those we have lost through war and conflict. Photo - Graeme Manning Come and join us! #sytm #hmssheffield #openday

Last night my Nigerian-American friend, Lotos Ada sent me a text in Igbo, her native language. "Ndewo," she said. It means greetings, or hello. She's learning Igbo language "small, small," she said, and she's enjoying the journey. And she also said she's been enjoying my social media posts about my family. I promised her I would do more posts about my family. So, here's another one. As I flipped through a folder in my bedroom thinking of what to share, I found this picture of my son, Malcolm, and my grandson Jakari. I love this photo: so much love, so much joy. I took this photograph about 18 years ago when Malcolm was standing outside our home talking to his buddy, Junior, who also had a son in his arms. I think about the power of transformation when I look at this photo. Jakari is now a freshman in college in Oregon. Malcolm is a successful businessman and father of two daughters and two sons. Malcolm was the catalyst for my spiritual transformation that led me to my initiation into Yoruba spiritual tradition of Nigeria many years ago. I said yes to transformation. Malcolm said yes to transformation too. I hope you will also yes to transformation. In this season of so much global conflict, endless wars and cycles of hate and injustice, it's important to focus our attention on what we can do, who we love, who loves us, who we can influence, and what legacy we wish to leave. Our children need us; the earth needs us, and we all need each other. I hope you find something in your day today that can fill your spirit with a bit more joy and love. CASE PROFILE Stella Farrugia was reported missing on Thursday 18 October 1984 by her boyfriend. He told police he last saw her at their home on Seaview Road, Henley Beach, the day before. There has not been a confirmed sighting of Stella since. The 18-year old has been described as outgoing, kind, and generous, but also a little na√Øve and easily led. The teenager had been raised in Sunshine, Victoria, and was the youngest child of Michael and Rose Farrugia who immigrated to Australia from Malta in the late-1950s. Her parents held strong beliefs on family matters arising from their traditional Maltese origins, with these conservative views often in conflict with those of the wider Australian community at the time, which often resulted in conflict within the family, particularly between Stella and her parents. It was against this backdrop that in late 1983 Stella unexpectedly moved to Queensland to stay with her older sister, Christine, who was newly married and living in Cairns. Stella got into a relationship and the young couple moved to Adelaide in 1984. The couple stayed at a number of addresses before moving to Henley Beach. After the relationship became strained, they split up and Stella moved in with another man, Wojciech Kubale, who reported her missing. Mr Kubale, who died in 2010, told police that he had been out for the day and came home to find her dog, bank books and personal possessions all at the flat ‚Äì but no sign of her. Initially police didn‚Äôt consider the matter suspicious ‚Äì they conducted inquiries but thought she had simply taken off. There was a suggested history of domestic violence in connection with both relationships, but there were no reports to police so it is hard to gauge to what extent. During this period she had written to her sister, demanding she make contact by a specific date and saying if she didn‚Äôt she would cut off all ties. That date came and went before her sister got around to replying, but sadly did not receive a response from Stella. It wasn‚Äôt until her boyfriend contacted the family to ask where she was that her disappearance was considered in a more concerning light and some weeks later they also reported her missing to the Sunshine Police. Another mysterious element to the case was that for several years after her disappearance Stella‚Äôs family received irregular phone calls where the caller did not speak when the phone was answered. The number of calls each year tapered off over time, finally stopping five or six years after she disappeared. Police have examined a number of properties, including the one at Mt Torrens where she stayed with her first boyfriend before moving to Henley Beach, but found no sign of her. Police believe there are two possible explanations in this case ‚Äì that Stella deliberately chose to move away and break all ties with her family, possibly with the assistance of someone who had offered to support her, or that she met with foul play. With pleas for information spanning many years, it seems more likely that she is deceased, given that she has not made contact with police or her family. Both of her boyfriends from that time remain persons of interest in the case, albeit one of them is now deceased. A reward of up to $200,000 is on offer to anyone who provides information leading to the recovery of her remains or information leading to a conviction in the case. Anyone with information can anonymously contact Crime Stoppers at https://crimestopperssa.com.au:=:https://crimestopperssa.com.au/ or freecall 1800 333 000. #CrimeStoppers #Anonymous #charity

One week into the war erupting in Israel and Gaza, social media is inducing a fog of war surpassing previous clashes in the region ‚Äî one that‚Äôs shaping how panicked citizens and a global public view the conflict.

Social media has long played a critical role in battles in the area. During the 11-day war between Israel and Hamas in 2021, posts of carnage in Gaza rallied the public to the Palestinian cause. Researchers say increased internet access and the spread of smartphones enabled a watershed moment, revealing how tech platforms could show the horror and human toll of such events.

But now, tech platforms, diminished from waves of layoffs, have receded from policing falsehoods, disinformation and hate speech online. And unlike in 2021, Palestinians in Gaza are already losing access to the internet, compromising their ability to tell their story.

A six-year-old Palestinian-American boy's last words were "mom, I'm fine" after he was stabbed to death in a suspected hate crime in Illinois over the weekend, his uncle has said.
 
Police have said Wadea and his mother, Hanaan Shahin, who is being treated in the hospital after suffering "over a dozen stab wounds", were targeted "due to their being Muslims and the ongoing Middle Eastern conflict involving Hamas and Israelis".
 
In Plainfield Township, Will County, about 40 miles (64 km) southwest of Chicago, their landlord attacked them on Saturday. The boy was stabbed 26 times, while Ms. Shahin, 32, suffered multiple wounds. Ms. Shahin was unable to attend the funeral while she was treated in the hospital but is expected to survive.
 
Mahmoud Yousef, Wadea's uncle, said in a news conference outside the mosque: "He's a six-year-old kid. As with any other six-year-old kid, he likes to play games. He's a very kind kid. He likes to jump up and down."
 
Mr. Yousef added, "We received a text message from his mom saying that when he was stabbed, his last words to her were, 'Mom, I'm fine.' You know what? He is fine. He's in a better place."

Dear Friends,

Today, I speak to you with a heart heavy as lead, struggling to hold back tears. In Palestine, a human tragedy is unfolding that defies comprehension.

In just the past week, over 6,000 bombs have shattered the fragile peace of this region, more than what the entire United States dropped on Afghanistan in a year. Families have been torn from their homes, and now, two million souls are huddled together in an overcrowded corner of Gaza. The one route of escape, the Egyptian border, has been cruelly reduced to rubble.

Palestine, already stripped of electricity and water, now faces the insufferable agony of white phosphorus contamination. Hospitals overflow with the wounded and the deceased, and they've even asked to evacuate the hospitals. But how can they evacuate with casualties, including tiny babies? The very places meant to provide healing have become targets themselves.

Ambulance vans, once symbols of salvation, have become targets as well. The roads are lined with lifeless bodies, and there's no space left to provide them a dignified resting place.
Even a warehouse of the International Aid Campaign(IAC), a beacon of hope in the darkest of times, has not been spared the wrath of violence.

What cuts deepest is the knowledge that we seem to have learned nothing from our shared history. The world stands by, silent witnesses to this suffering. It's not about religion; it's about our shared humanity.

This, dear friends, is not just a conflict; it is a desperate cry for empathy and compassion. We must stand together, across all borders and beliefs, to demand an immediate end to this devastating crisis.

With a heart heavy,

While this is not a political page, I cannot remain silent about the suffering of the children involved in the current conflict between Israel and Gaza.

It‚Äôs time that we normalise standing up for humanity without taking sides, to condemn all violence and protect all human lives equally. 

Hamas killed around 1200 innocent Israelis, some of them children, and took many hostages which is an atrocity that I condemn. All hostages should be returned. Israeli children are currently living in fear. But in response, the Israeli government decided to cut off food, water and electricity to 2 million Palestinians, half of which are children, and are carpet bombing their land with thousands of bombs. While the target might be Hamas, the civilian population is suffering though a living hell.

Israel should absolutely defend its people from Hamas, but indiscriminately bombing and starving an entire population is not proportionate. 

The UN has called this a crime against humanity and a violation of international law. 

The long-term solution is to see all of humanity as one people. Until we genuinely feel this in our hearts, there will be no love because minds will continue to divide and fight.
