Late Tuesday, a missile hit al-Ahli hospital in Gaza City, resulting in hundreds of deaths.

According to Gaza's Health Ministry, people were using the hospital both for medical treatment and as a shelter when the missile struck. Hamas has been known to use these hospitals as headquarters, and a place to also store weapons.

Who did it? Israel says the explosion was due to a failed Palestinian Islamic Jihad missile launch. This is backed up by Arab news outlets and journalists who note the blast happened right after Islamic Jihad said it was firing missiles. 

Context: This wouldn't be the first time a missile mishap from Palestinian extremists led to fatalities in Gaza. Failed launches have previously hit within the territory, killing Palestinians.

üì© Most of our fast and uncensored coverage of the conflict (with exclusive geopolitical analysis) will be in our daily email. Comment ‚ÄúJOIN‚Äù to get the updates and bypass the algorithm. These stories won‚Äôt be on Instagram.

Our hearts go out to the Palestians and Israelis who have suffered such devastating loss ‚Äî not only for the thousands of Gazans and Israelis, following a horrific attack by Hamas over the last week, but for generations of Palestinians who have lived decades under occupation. 

Our most powerful tool now is to hold onto our humanity and educate ourselves, particularly as British people on this colonial history. 

Less than a year ago @earthrise.studio and I were on the ground in Gaza with @icrc to work on a documentary exploring the links between climate change and conflict. 

We must remember that these moments don‚Äôt happen in a vacuum, rather they hold up a mirror to society and are products of complex histories. When we went to Gaza last year, we documented how half a century of occupation have made Gazans even more vulnerable to the impacts of climate change. Vulnerability often compounds vulnerability.

Gazans now face a complete blockade from electricity, energy, and aid ‚Äî while undergoing indiscriminate bombing. We must not look away.

Too often we're reactive because we're hurt while also using our anger to control others.

I am of the belief the anger is also showing you where you're being disrespected. 

And because I believe in allowing people to have "bad days", we can give them grace and see how they move as we go forward.

Letting them cook allows you to take a moment, breathe and watch how they handle situations where they think you're not paying attention or they have the upper hand because you're not being reactive.

After all, they're used to women/partners who "go off" and now you're showing them how easy you are to control.

They want to dip out and spend time with another love interest? 

They know to start an argument, because you'll get reactive and curse them out - they disappear for days to punish you as they get the time to spend with someone else. 

This explains the random, dumb arguments that seemingly pop up out of the blue.

The disappearing for days and ignoring your calls is your "let them cook" moment.

Now you're seeing how they handle conflict.

But when you're being reactive, angry, controlling, demanding and giving ultimatums - you're not paying attention to what they'd rather do.

And this is where acceptance slides in. 

In doing this you learn to accept people for who they are without personalizing it.

Detach with love, because we're not doing this anymore.

Because there's a life where you wake up completely at peace, anxiety free, not hung up on someone's inability to call you back in a respectable time period, using your pain against you or tolerating head games that leave you angry and confused.

That's where my Inner Circle comes in.

üåü This is your invitation to join a sisterhood of healing women who are rewriting their narratives, while giving you the tools to transform your relationships, most importantly the one with yourself.

Imagine no longer falling into these nasty cycles of painful relationships while having a tribe of resilient women by your side who are on the same journey as you are.

In protest over the purported airstrike, Palestinian President Mahmoud Abbas canceled his participation in a meeting with Biden, Jordan‚Äôs King Abdullah II and Egypt‚Äôs president set for Wednesday in Amman, Jordan to discuss the war. 

Later, Jordan‚Äôs foreign minister told state-run television that Jordan had canceled the summit, saying that the war between Israel and Hamas was ‚Äúpushing the region to the brink.‚Äù He said the meeting would be postponed.

The comments emerged as Biden boarded the plane for his Mideast trip, which in part aims to prevent the war from sparking a broader regional conflict.

I was always wishy-washy in my relationships. I was ‚Äúcommitted‚Äù to my partner but subconsciously had one foot out the door in case it didn‚Äôt work out. In a sense, this was helpful because I always had savings, kept my individuality, and maintained my independence. On the other hand, I wasn‚Äôt fully invested in the future of our relationship, was self-absorbed in my needs, and anything that went ‚Äúwrong‚Äù made me question the entirety of our love. We were always on thin ice.

When I learned about my attachment style years ago, it made sense why I was so protective of myself. My belief that love would abandon or betray me caused much of the ambivalence I was experiencing.

Though I thought I was doing myself a favor by taking this protective approach, I realized it was causing so much of the anxiety, disconnection, and conflict we were experiencing.

Though I still have doubts that surface occasionally, I make the conscious choice (daily) to commit to my relationship values (i.e., growth, commitment, partnership, support, individuality, respect, communication, honesty, to name a few).

This doesn‚Äôt mean I‚Äôm now susceptible to being mistreated or taken advantage of. It just means I can be fully committed while knowing my boundaries.

Understanding what‚Äôs most important to us can help redirect our attention when we feel lost, uncertain, or in doubt.

*If you need support navigating relationship anxiety and developing skills to create secure relationships, you can learn more about coaching with me 1:1 via the link in my bio. Limited spaces available.

Cognitive dissonance can contribute to the development of a trauma bond, especially in relationships with narcissists. A trauma bond is a strong emotional connection that forms between a person and someone who is harmful or abusive. In the context of narcissistic relationships, the inconsistency between the narcissist's charming facade and their hurtful behavior creates cognitive dissonance. This internal conflict, combined with intermittent reinforcement of positive attention, can deepen emotional ties and make it difficult for the person to break away from the relationship, despite the harm caused. The trauma bond often involves a cycle of idealization, devaluation, and intermittent reinforcement that keeps the person emotionally attached, even in the face of negative experiences.

Do you feel like your desire for your partner disappeared after you had a baby? 
 
Many new moms experience fluctuation in desire. This makes sense‚Äìwe‚Äôre navigating hormone shifts, sleep deprivation, and a vulnerable time for our mental health. 
 
But research shows that there‚Äôs another big factor at play in low sex drive for moms‚Äìthe division of labor. 
 
A recent study suggests that when women carry an unfair proportion of household labor, they often have a significantly lower sexual desire for their partner.* 
 
When moms are carrying more than their fair share of the invisible load, they might come to view their partner as a dependent and build resentment over the distribution of labor. (Which doesn‚Äôt exactly set the mood for desire or arousal!) 
 
The good news is that if you find yourself in that situation, it isn‚Äôt hopeless! 
 
When we become aware of what is leading to resentment and conflict, it becomes easier to address it productively.

Whether you realize it or not, you‚Äôre always in a growth process.

This process is defined by the relationship between your self-awareness right now, and a new, more expanded version of yourself trying to emerge.

Sometimes, the meeting of these two processes leads to an easy, liberating transformation; you sense a needed change and are able to do it. 

But more often, your current consciousness blocks the required change. This creates conflict, tension, and pain.

If your mind can‚Äôt accept, is afraid of, isn‚Äôt ready yet, or is simply unaware of how you need to grow, it forces the basic emotion driving your growth to mutate.

Instead of experiencing power or creativity or playfulness or whatever is trying to emerge into your consciousness, the raw emotion behind the new process manifests as a disturbance, a problem, a ‚Äúsymptom.‚Äù

The fundamental emotion driving your issue is right, but it manifests in a negative way. 

Conventional mental health practice misses the mark by just trying to suppress your pain‚Äîthe disturbing manifestation of your process. Doing so, throws out the baby with the bathwater.

Instead, you must learn how to reverse the mutation, uncover the hidden emotion driving your feelings, thoughts, and actions. This leads to liberation and expansion‚Äîthe true purpose of your problems. Just trying to get rid of your issue may reduce discomfort but it kills your growth.

Your problem is your process!

Behind your nasty inner critic, impossible relationship, depression, anxiety, attention deficit, delusions, mood swings, health issues, or boredom is an unseen emotion, a felt sense, a creative power, a new understanding and self-awareness pushing forth, trying with all its blind might to become a conscious awareness in your psyche.

No matter how bad your problem is, don‚Äôt dismiss it as a meaningless error in your life, an ‚Äúillness,‚Äù a pathology to ‚Äúdiagnose‚Äù and ‚Äútreat"; always keep faith and belief in that fact that it has a meaningful message, and keep working to connect with its potent, hidden emotion.

To learn more, listen to the Dr. Zwig Show.

Days before Hamas launched its assault on Israel and brutally massacred hundreds of civilians, I half-joked to a friend that ‚Äúno one cares about the Middle East anymore.‚Äù I said this as a lament. I spoke too soon. About a week before Hamas‚Äôs attack, U.S. national security adviser Jake Sullivan boasted to an audience that under the Biden administration‚Äôs watch, ‚Äúthe Middle East region is quieter today than it has been in two decades.‚Äù He also spoke too soon.

The Middle East never stays quiet. If the deeper sources of violent conflict in the region are left to fester, any peace and quiet will pass as quickly as it came. A dose of humility is in order.

By chance, as Israel intensified its bombardment of Gaza, I found myself at a summit on ‚Äúintellectual humility‚Äù hosted by the John Templeton Foundation. It felt self-indulgent to discuss a philosophical concept with seemingly little relevance to the conflict. When it came to life and death, did any of this really matter? But what I found was that it did.

Intellectual humility is a trait and a practice that allows one to accept their own limitations. Even if we think we are right, it entails holding open the possibility that we might be wrong. But on a deeper level, humility involves the recognition that the truth itself is more complicated than it might first appear.

The search for truth, even if one finds it, should not involve rigidity. We are all a product of our environments. When it comes to Israel and Palestine in particular, we bring our own preconceptions to any debate ‚Äî our own selective read of history and our own developed sense of injustice. This is not about a disagreement over facts; it‚Äôs about how to interpret them. My hope is that more Americans will understand this, considering how much we disagree with one another over our own founding as a nation.

A 6-year-old boy is dead, and his mother seriously wounded after they were both stabbed more than a dozen times due to their Muslim faith Saturday in a Chicago suburb.

Around 11:38 a.m., deputies with the Will County Sheriff's Office responded to a home located near the intersection of S. Lincoln Highway and Lily Cache Road in Plainfield for a report of a stabbing.

A 32-year-old woman had called 9-1-1 and stated her landlord had attacked her with a knife, and that she ran into the bathroom and continued to fight off her attacker as she dialed 9-1-1.

When officers arrived at the scene, they located the suspect ‚Äì identified as 71-year-old Joseph M. Czuba ‚Äì sitting on the ground outside the home with a laceration to his forehead. He was transported to an area hospital for treatment.

Inside the home, in a bedroom, police say they located two victims who had multiple stab wounds to their chest, torso, and upper extremities. The 32-year-old woman was hospitalized in serious condition with over a dozen stab wounds to her body. A 6-year-old boy had also suffered 26 stab wounds throughout his body and was pronounced dead at the hospital.

The knife used in the attack was seven inches long and serrated.

Czuba was treated and released from the hospital, and taken by police for questioning. He was charged with first-degree murder, attempted first-degree murder, two counts of hate crime and aggravated battery with a deadly weapon.

"Detectives were able to determine that both victims in this brutal attack were targeted by the suspect due to them being Muslim and the on-going Middle Eastern conflict involving Hamas and the Israelis," according to the Will County Sheriff's Office.

The weapon used in this "heinous crime" was recovered, police said.

The investigation is ongoing.üëÄ

Last week I posted here reflecting on why the atrocities committed by Hammas on innocent Israeli men, women and children were similar to 9/11, arguing that the terrorists were seeking to provoke Israel into anger as a means of scuppering the relationships that Netanyahu had been building  between Isreal and Sunni Arab nations in the region. Today I want to talk about the ways that the Black Saturday attack was not like 9/11.

In September 2001, America was targeted by al-Qaeda terrorists as a proxy for western imperialism. The evidence is found in the ‚ÄòLetter to America‚Äô that Osama Bin Laden posted after the event to justify ordering such a horrific attack. That he included ‚Äòenvironmental destruction‚Äô in the list reasons why America deserved to be attacked was a sign that he was desperate to convince people that he was right to order such an atrocity.

Hammas felt no need to offer an explanation for why they attacked Israel, and it was not because no words could justify the terrible acts of violence that they committed that day. Israel is not a proxy target to Hammas. It is a state which has been in conflict with the Palestinian people for the past 70 years. Sometimes that war has been one of low level attrition, sometimes it has been all-out combat. The fact that Israel has been forced to become a highly militarised society is a product of this reality.

I stress again that this does not mean that the Hammas attacks were justified. Directly targeting civilians, in terror or war, cannot be justified. The point that I am seeking to make is that, horrific though it may be, Black Saturday didn‚Äôt just appear out of a blue sky like the planes that hit the Twin Towers. The world has watched this uneven conflict play out on our tv screens over the past decades. We have witnessed the cycle of terrorism and retribution over and over again. We know what is coming next. The humanity that causes us to weep for the victims of Black Saturday also makes us fear for the people of Gaza.

Can you ever really lose yourself? These last few weeks have been really difficult for me. I landed up at a terrible retreat centre, which threw me into severe malnutrition and totally dulled my energy. More on cautions with new age spirituality which is disconnected from the real traditions very soon. It‚Äôs been astrologically heavy, we have world conflict, I always aim to show up and serve my best but the events of the past few weeks - for the first time in my whole adult life, have made me feel like maybe I lost myself. 

It took some time, but my energy started to get better. My memory started coming  back, yet when you go through something destructive - it takes time to heal. And there are times in life where you really feel like, you lost your spirit. And nothing can feel worse. 

Comfortably numb - as Pink Floyd said. 

But amidst all the duality, there are lessons and a shedding of the old. A shedding of the paradigms we once related to. The acknowledge of what doesn‚Äôt suit our spirit and soul, and the spaces where we feel most at home. 

That, despite how much something or an experience brings you down, there is always and ALWAYS simultaneously a much higher good being birthed too. There is always light, and eternal light of the heart, the beautiful connection with life, nature, our dharma and deities. 

Intrinsically, you can never lose yourself. People may come and go but you can never lose what‚Äôs real. So no matter how much reality seems to be warping - the words, ‚Äòthere‚Äôs no such thing as a bad trip‚Äô truly make sense. 

Moving through the karmic cycles, surrendering trust in our divine origin and opening, opening even further to embrace the overwhelming love of the universe that we call life.

The anti-zionist agitation against Israel is not just a criticism of the state and the nation. Quite the contrary. Those who claim "Palestine solidarity" are not concerned with the liberation of Palestinian civilians from the conditions in which humans are degraded, enslaved and abandoned. On 17th October, the 11th day of Israel's bombardments on the besieged Gaza Strip, Israel bombed the Al Ali hospital in Gaza, killing more than 500 people including patients, doctors & those seeking refuge.

Gaza is home to 2.3 million Palestinians (1.1 million children) and is one of the world's most densely populated places. Israel has held it under siege for 17 years. In the last 11 days Israel has dropped thousands of bombs on the imprisoned population, estimated to be the equivalent force of a quarter of a nuclear bomb.

Human rights experts have also confirmed the use of the internationally-banned weapon, white phosphorus.

On 15 October 2023, over 800 scholars and practitioners of international law, conflict studies and genocide studies signed a public statement warning of the possibility of genocide being perpetrated by Israeli forces against Palestinians in the Gaza Strip.

I've seen too many video of fathers digging through the rubble to find their kids, calmly holding lifeless bodies and reading the shahada for the ones they lost, looking for pieces of their child as they try not to fall into a million pieces themselves.

This is not a conflict. It is not a war. It is a genocide.

This is a picture of my children and a picture of another woman‚Äôs children. 

The last few days have been full of turmoil for me. The images I have seen circulated have given me the most vivid nightmares. I have consistently woken up panicked and sweating having seen my own children coming to the same fate as those involved in the war. It is so indescribably painful. We live our lives cushioned and comforted by the roof above our head the food we eat and the stability a life without conflict gifts us. I visited the region in my twenties and understand the complexity of the politics. 
My heart bleeds for all those suffering, a pain that is beyond the pain that I can even begin to conceive.  I keep asking myself ‚ÄòWhat if?‚Äô What if that child was mine, what if I was living a life where there was no guarantee of tomorrow? 

Praying to my creator that humanity can prevail and no human has to experience this hell on earth.

Prayer for Peace‚Å†
‚Å†
Lord God of peace, hear our prayer!‚Å†
We have tried so many times and over so many years to resolve our conflicts by our own powers and by the force of our arms. How many moments of hostility and darkness have we experienced; how much blood has been shed; how many lives have been shattered; how many hopes have been buried‚Ä¶ But our efforts have been in vain.‚Å†
‚Å†
Now, Lord, come to our aid! Grant us peace, teach us peace; guide our steps in the way of peace. Open our eyes and our hearts, and give us the courage to say: "Never again war!"; "With war everything is lost". Instill in our hearts the courage to take concrete steps to achieve peace.‚Å†
‚Å†
Lord, God of Abraham, God of the Prophets, God of Love, you created us and you call us to live as brothers and sisters. Give us the strength daily to be instruments of peace; enable us to see everyone who crosses our path as our brother or sister. Make us sensitive to the plea of our citizens who entreat us to turn our weapons of war into implements of peace, our trepidation into confident trust, and our quarreling into forgiveness.‚Å†
‚Å†
Keep alive within us the flame of hope, so that with patience and perseverance we may opt for dialogue and reconciliation. In this way may peace triumph at last, and may the words "division", "hatred" and "war" be banished from the heart of every man and woman. Lord, defuse the violence of our tongues and our hands. Renew our hearts and minds, so that the word which always brings us together will be "brother", and our way of life will always be that of: Shalom, Peace, Salaam!‚Å†
‚Å†
Amen.

Your relationship with yourself dictates the quality of your relationships with everyone else.

In a speech delivered before the European Parliament in Strasbourg, France, Armenian Prime Minister Nikol Pashinyan expressed deep regret over the failure of the international community to prevent the ethnic cleansing of Armenians in Nagorno-Karabakh by Azerbaijan. Pashinyan's speech shed light on the dire situation in the region, stating that over 100,000 Armenians were forced to flee their homes in Nagorno-Karabakh within a single week, amidst the inaction of Russian peacekeepers and the indifference of global powers.
Pashinyan lamented the lack of effective action despite numerous warnings, international rulings, and resolutions passed by bodies such as the International Court of Justice, the European Parliament, and the Parliamentary Assembly of the Council of Europe. He highlighted the blatant disregard for these warnings, resulting in the mass exodus of Armenians from Nagorno-Karabakh. The Prime Minister emphasized that Azerbaijan's intentions to make life impossible for Armenians in Nagorno-Karabakh were crystal clear, leading to the tragic displacement of thousands of families.
Armenia's leader criticized the international community's surprise at the depopulation of Nagorno-Karabakh in September, asserting that his country had consistently warned about Azerbaijan‚Äôs intentions since December 2022. He expressed his disappointment at the lack of support from Armenia's security allies during the crisis, revealing that instead of assistance, calls for a coup against his democratically elected government were made. Pashinyan condemned these actions as attacks on Armenia‚Äôs sovereignty and democracy, orchestrated through foreign aggression and hybrid technologies.
The Armenian Prime Minister thanked the European Parliament for acknowledging the dire situation faced by the forcibly displaced Armenians in Nagorno-Karabakh. He called for future efforts to protect the rights of these individuals and ensure their safety, despite the challenges posed by the ongoing conflict.

Regardless of one's religious or cultural background, it is imperative as humans that we cannot turn a blind eye to the dire situation unfolding in Palestine. We cannot, and must not, stay silent; we must talk about it openly. This is not a 'complicated conflict,' nor is it a situation that necessitates excessive nuance. It's not a 'geopolitical event' that requires us to make vague condemnations of 'bad actors' on 'both sides.'

What we are witnessing is nothing short of a genocide. The Israeli state's actions against the Palestinian people are unequivocally a genocide, and it is occurring right before our eyes. There is no room for ambiguity; it is a genocide, carried out by the Israeli state against the Palestinian population. You don't need to read between the lines: Israel has openly, with little resistance from so-called liberal democracies, severed Gaza's access to essential resources such as water, food, and electricity. This has left more than two million Palestinians, including a million children, deprived of even the most basic necessities for life.

Consider this staggering fact: in just six days, Israel has dropped 6,000 bombs on the besieged coastal enclave, home to 2.3 million Palestinians, half of whom are innocent children. Israel's use of internationally banned white phosphorus, the heartbreaking deaths of babies as young as seven days old, and their orders for 1.1 million people to evacuate their homes within 24 hours, followed by bombings that injure and kill those attempting to flee, are all reprehensible acts.

What we are witnessing is nothing less than ethnic cleansing in full view of the world. We cannot, in good conscience, look away from these unspeakable horrors. It is our moral duty to discuss this crisis openly and take decisive action to bring it to an end. Humanity demands nothing less.

Do you have a queer memory? You can immortalise it by dropping a pin on a digital map of the world via @queeringthemap ... but for the residents of war-torn Gaza, the platform has become a heartbreaking testament of their pain.

Queering the Map is a digital space that allows LGBTQ+ people to tag a place anywhere on the planet and writing anonymous messaging describing what a location means to them. So far, there are over half a million memories pinned all over the globe, affirming that queer history is everywhere.

With Gaza under bloody siege, recent memories of queer people caught in the conflict have emerged, and they are gut-wrenching.

‚ÄúI‚Äôve always imagined you and me sitting in the sun, hand in hand, free at last," one message read, from Jabalia, a few kilometers north of Gaza city. "We spoke of all the places we would go if we could. Yet you are gone now."

‚ÄúIf I had known that bombs raining down on us would take you from me, I would have gladly told the world how I adored you more than anything. I‚Äôm sorry I was a coward.‚Äù

‚ÄúI don‚Äôt know how long I will live so just want this to be my memory here before I die," another from North Gaza, which is currently being evacuated, read. "I am not going to leave my home, come what may. My biggest regret is not kissing this one guy. He died two days back. We had told each other how much we like each other and I was too shy to kiss last time. He died in the bombing. I think a big part of me died too. And soon I will be dead. To younus, I will kiss you in heaven.‚Äù

‚ÄúA place were I kissed my first crush," another yet reads. "Being gay in Gaza is hard but somehow it was fun. I made out with a lot of boys in my neighborhood thought everyone is gay to some level.‚Äù

The platform has also attracted a flooding of support from other nations and religions, with one self-described "gay Jew" leaving a simple message of "Free Palestine" pinned in the heart of the conflict zone.

The website has sadly also been subject to cyberattacks, and has been down for several weeks according to Twitter/X users. Still, these messages remind us that civilians should never (but often are) caught in the crossfires of war.

A gruesome video of a man beheading a child went viral on social media last week ‚Äî initially shared by a premium or verified Twitter account as evidence of Hamas‚Äô attack on Israel. The video was viewed by millions online, and shared with hashtags ‚ÄòIslamIsTheProblem‚Äô and ‚ÄòIsraelUnderAttack‚Äô.

But was it a video of the escalated Israel-Palestine conflict? Fact-checkers found that the clip was unrelated to Israel or Palestinian militant group Hamas, and was instead shot in Syria in 2016. The false claims were quickly debunked by fact-checkers using multiple technological tools ‚Äî but the damage had already been done.

Credible information has been collateral damage in the Israel-Palestine conflict, in which at least 2,670 Palestinians and 1,400 Israelis have been killed so far. 

Within days of the escalation that began on October 8, fact-checkers reported being faced with a huge volume of misinformation and disinformation. 

The fact-checkers who spoke to Newslaundry called the barrage of misinformation ‚Äúunprecedented,‚Äù with many pointing to the role of X, formerly known as Twitter, in fuelling it. 

Read the full report by @tanishka_s on newslaundry.com, link in bio.

I was asked recently why I was not adding my voice to the chorus on current affairs. (This is an excerpt from my weekly newsletter ‚Äúthe Honest Files‚Äù - link in bio)

I come from a country where the words ‚Äúceasefire‚Äù, ‚Äúterrorism‚Äù and ‚Äúpeace process‚Äù were as much a part of my childhood as words like ‚Äúcartoon‚Äù and ‚Äúplayground‚Äù. It‚Äôs not that I don‚Äôt have thoughts. 

It‚Äôs that I‚Äôm keenly aware of how easy it is to misspeak. To be misinformed. To contribute to the spread of a harmful and false narrative. 

I lived for 26 years immersed in a situation with some significant parallels to the current conflict‚Ä¶and I managed to misunderstand it completely. Only now do I realise that I failed to grasp important nuances. 

Trust me when I say that most of us should probably close our mouths. We might regret our vocal support of causes we don‚Äôt fully comprehend. I know that‚Äôs my experience in the N. Ireland conflict. 

Worth also saying you can silently be active. Today I supported @humanite.peace.collective . I‚Äôm never going to regret trying to provide shelter, food and water to non-combatants. Something to consider if you also want to make a difference rather than just make a noise.

Scoop: The White House has been discussing the possibility of using military force if Hezbollah joins the war in Gaza and attacks Israel with its huge arsenal of rockets, three U.S. officials and one Israeli official with knowledge of the situation tell Axios.

Why it matters: Lebanon-based Hezbollah joining the war would dramatically escalate the Middle East's worst conflict in decades ‚Äî raising the likelihood of mass civilian casualties in Israel and Lebanon and possibly drawing in the U.S.

‚Ä¢ The Israeli military ‚Äî now focused mostly on Gaza ‚Äî would have a significantly more difficult time fighting on two fronts simultaneously while missiles rain down on its bases and Israel's population centers.

State of play: Since the Gaza war began Oct. 7, tensions between Israel and Hezbollah have been increasing, with daily skirmishes between the parties along the Israel-Lebanon border.

‚Ä¢ Iran-backed Hezbollah has fired rockets and anti-tank missiles at Israeli outposts and forces on the border in recent days, while Israeli airstrikes have hit Hezbollah positions. Several Hezbollah operatives and several IDF soldiers have been killed.

‚Ä¢ At the same time, both sides have managed to keep the exchange of fire on a relatively low level, avoiding all-out fighting.

‚Ä¢ Hezbollah so far has refrained from sending its operatives for a ground assault or from firing its long-range, accurate missiles at Israeli targets.

Visual Riff: Expressions of Grief

These posts were prepared before the recent Hamas terror rampage into Israel and the resulting ferocious Israeli attacks on Gaza. I've seen this film way too many times, but this episode has taken the hostilities to another level. 

Since I first started photographic reporting in Palestine and Israel in 1992, I've watched as both sides have become more coarse, hateful, and dehumanizing towards each other. When I began my project on messianic Jewish Settlers in the West Bank in 1994, I was told how Palestinian families in nearby villages would bring their newborn sons to the rabbi in the adjacent settlement to get circumcised. That sort of cooperation and coexistence would be unthinkable now.

We need an end to war, violence, and the other atrocities we've witnessed over the past days. I'm holding my breath that Israel finds the strength and humanity to resist the complete destruction of northern Gaza. Exacting retribution will only continue this cycle of violence.

The power of pause lies in its ability to bring clarity, reflection, and a sense of control to our actions and words. Taking a moment to pause can help us make more deliberate and thoughtful decisions, fostering better communication and understanding in various situations.

The benefits of incorporating pauses in your life include:

1. Improved decision-making: Pausing allows you to think more clearly and make well-considered choices.

2. Better communication: Pauses help you listen actively and respond thoughtfully in conversations.

3. Stress reduction: Taking a moment to pause can lower stress levels and promote relaxation.

4. Enhanced creativity: Pauses provide space for new ideas and insights to emerge.

5. Increased self-awareness: Pausing allows for introspection and self-reflection.

6. Conflict resolution: It helps prevent impulsive reactions in conflicts, leading to more productive resolutions.

7. Health benefits: Pausing can reduce anxiety and improve overall well-being.

8. Time management: It aids in prioritizing tasks and staying focused on what's important.

9. Improved relationships: Pauses enable empathy and understanding in interactions with others.

10. Mindfulness and presence: Pausing promotes being fully present in the moment, leading to a more fulfilling life.

"What does the concept of 'pausing' mean to you, and how has it impacted your life? Share a moment when taking a pause made a significant difference. #PowerOfPause"

Legacies are always a huge burden to carry. Those left behind get crushed under its weight. Smita "Smi" Patil left us with crushed by the weight of her memories, overwhelmed by her standout performances and a feeling of  an unbearable ache. 
The same ache returns when you see her character of Kavita Sanyal begging Pooja(Shabana Azmi) to leave Inder(Kulbushan) in that heart-breaking scene in #Arth. Kavita Sanyal's descent into hell was a close glimpse into relationships in showbiz as much as an understanding of a fractured mind.
The adaptation of Hansa Wadkar‚Äôs life was again as much an exploration of the whimsical ways of showbiz as much as it was a voyage into a woman's troubled journey. Barely 22 years of age, her portrayal mirrored the acute insecurities of women taking a stance without being unnecessary judgemental.
Empowerment was Smi's thing. She was affected by the world she inhabited. You see that concern In Sulabha Mahajan in Jabbar Patel's Umbartha. Sulabha‚Äôs need for self expression makes her leave the comfort of home and take up a job as warden in a rehabilitation home for women. This film could have been Smi's alter-ego speaking. 
Her role as Najma in Sagar Sarhadi's Bazaar also reflected that search for meaning.. It's only after her brother's fianc√©e commits suicide, she has a wake up call. Smi employed her eyes to dramatic effect and despite the somewhat awry Hyderabadi accent, her Najma in Bazaar is as solid as its heart-rending. 
Barely 29, how she entered the skin of 50 plus Hanumi in #Giddh is her triumph as a performer. You see that conflict in Rabindra Dharmaraj's Chakra. As Amma who tries to grapple a combative son and her various paramours, Smi's body language and sadness is compelling to watch.
Art for her indeed was a revelation of the truth. It was a quest. But as in the movies, the plot line changed. Happy birthday Smi, I  hope the angels will sing to you always.

Today in 1777, the Saratoga Campaign concludes. Fought along the Hudson River in New York and Vermont, this battle proved to be a turning point for the American Revolution. British General John Burgoyne‚Äôs intention was to separate New England from the Southern Colonies. At this early stage of the conflict, British forces had secured several victories, decreasing American morale. With a victory at Saratoga, however, some of this morale was restored, and France entered the war on behalf of the Continental Army. Lasting four months, the campaign consisted of Continental soldiers, the Vermont Republic, and the Oneida Tribe fighting against the forces of Britain and their loyal tribes. Benedict Arnold, the General who later betrayed Continental forces and joined the British Army, played a significant role in this battle. The victory at Saratoga resulted in the formation of the Franco-American alliance, paving the way for the British surrender at Yorktown, Virginia. The painting featured is ‚ÄúSurrender of General Burgoyne,‚Äù by John Trumbull, and it is displayed in the US Capitol Rotunda. #todayinhistory #history

Official Statement on the Vote for Speaker of the House

This week, when members of the House of Representatives reconvene to vote for a speaker, they will have the opportunity to demonstrate their enduring commitment to our Constitutional system of government. While a handful of extremists have precipitated a crisis of leadership, an equally small number of courageous and reasonable actors have the opportunity to exhibit bipartisanship and restore faith in ethical governance. As leaders and members of Mormon Women for Ethical Government, we ask all members of Congress, regardless of party affiliation, to find a pathway to the election of a speaker who has proven they will support the peaceful transfer of power.

We are once again faced with a conflict within our governing bodies that would have previously seemed unthinkable. As citizens, we are asked to accept an impossible compromise ‚Äî tolerate congressional leaders who have worked to undermine a legitimate election, or risk having no functioning government at all. It is important for our elected representatives to see this compromise for what it is ‚Äî an extortionate lie.

Installing a speaker who previously voted against the certification of the 2020 election will compromise the security and stability of our nation. Those who worked to undermine the last election should not be trusted to oversee the next one. In the election for House leadership, it falls to members of the majority party to control their extreme factions. Key Republican members of the House must stand fast and work to elect a speaker who has demonstrated respect both for their colleagues and for legislative norms and processes. 

In addition, we earnestly plead with members of the Democratic caucus to work across the aisle with Republicans who are committed to upholding the rule of law. Any Democrat who votes to elect competent and ethical House leadership could reasonably claim to be a principled defender of good government, national security, fiscal responsibility, and respect for the individual citizens of this nation. These things must matter more than party politics.

This reflection focuses on the concept of God. Personally, I believe in an intelligent force that is the origin of everything in the universe, which I refer to as God. I perceive God as an energy of love and compassion, the essence of goodness and creation that resides within all living beings. 

This is why I don‚Äôt seek God in confined spaces or extravagant structures. The walls in such structures create physical and spiritual barriers between people and God. To truly experience God, one can connect by walking barefoot in nature, embracing a tree, pet, or another human being for three minutes. These actions can bring us closer to God, as God doesn‚Äôt require our admiration or worship, but rather wants us to embody his/her qualities and act accordingly.

During the distressing conflict between Israel and Palestine, I‚Äôve encountered videos from both sides claiming that God permits killing in his/her  name. I deeply question this notion. I firmly believe in one God. Do we possess different Gods? Is the Middle Eastern God distinct from the Western or East Asian God?

Instead of witnessing fights on my Instagram feed, let‚Äôs engage in discussions about God. Lately, we seem to have forgotten about God, as our hateful arguments render us Godless. 

So, my question is: where is God right now during this conflict? and what do you think God is contemplating when our self-centered minds assert that we are God‚Äôs most precious creation, made in his/her image? Yet, we behave as Godless beings. 

Please engage in a civilized and compassionate dialogue about this, devoid of hate. Perhaps by discussing God, we can remind ourselves that we came into this world to experience Godliness, not to harm and kill one another, as that aligns with the work of the Devil.

Is conflict a major problem in your marriage? This week over in my free Facebook group (link in bio to join) I'll be going live to continue the conversation on conflict. Specifically what to do when defensiveness shows up in your marriage. What do you do instead of defending yourself? What do you do if your partner is defensive? 

I takes two people to create a conflict, but it only takes one person to end it. 

A lot gets said about the importance of defending yourself. But consider the difference between defending yourself and standing up for yourself. 

Defence is part of a game. It is a you vs. me tactic and it has no place in a healthy marriage. 

If I have to defend myself against you, that means you are just that, against me.

If you are against me in that moment, and I am now defending myself, we are not working towards anything positive for the relationship. We are not creating connection, we are creating disconnection. 

When you learn to truly not engage in creating that disconnection in your marriage, the spiral downward stops. 

It is likely the number one thing you can do to turn the tides on conflict. 

To learn more about how to show up without defensiveness, become a member of the FB group for free by clicking the link in my bio, or send me a DM with the word "RECORDING" if you'd like me to send you the free workshop recording following the session. ‚ù§Ô∏è

Coming back for its second season on Oct. 29 on HBO and Max is its critically acclaimed series The Gilded Age,¬†created and written by¬†Julian Fellowes.

Den√©e Benton, Audra McDonald, John Douglas Thompson return as Peggy, Dorothy and Arthur Scott respectively. Sullivan Jones was promoted to regular status for Season 2 as¬†T. Thomas Fortune¬†¬†

Among the creative team are writer/executive producer Sonja Warfield and executive producer Salli Richardson-Whitfield

Erica Armstrong Dunbar serves as a co-executive producer/ historical consultant on the series.

The American Gilded Age was a period of immense economic change, of great conflict between the old ways and brand new systems, and of huge fortunes made and lost. Season two of THE GILDED AGE begins on Easter morning 1883, with the news that Bertha Russell's bid for a box at the Academy of Music has been rejected. Through the eight episodes of the season, we watch as Bertha challenges Mrs. Astor and the old system and works to not only gain a foothold in Society, but to potentially take a leading role in it. George Russell takes on his own battle with a growing union at his steel plant in Pittsburgh. In the Brook House, Marian continues her journey to find her way in the world secretly teaching at a girls school while much to everyone‚Äôs surprise Ada begins a new courtship. Of course, Agnes approves of none of it. In Brooklyn, the Scott family begins to heal from a shocking discovery, and Peggy taps into her activist spirit through her work with T. Thomas Fortune at the NY Globe.

What are you holding onto that‚Äôs setting you back?

The infantilization of our culture, coupled with the stamping out of any sense of a rite of passage, has engineered an almost unanimous stagnation among our young adults. 

There are common complaints of being unable to choose a life path, as if postponing their decision isn't a choice in itself.

Fundamentally, when you boil down the man who struggles with his own evolution, you are left with one thing.

An unresolved past.

A man who still identifies with the timid child shoved to the ground during a gym class.

A man whose heart remains shattered by the first woman who gave him attention.

A man who shies away from conflict, haunted by memories of his parents' contentious arguments.

These men may not consciously ruminate on these past pains, but they are fundamentally marked by them.

Preventing them from making decisions, fearing they could be put in harm's way again. 

Most men who navigate adulthood are stuck in these sands of their past.

Neurotically aware how a wrong choice could lead to catastrophe. 

Yet, they remain ignorant to the fact that their own inaction and ruminating is the very source of their suffering.

As the snake which cannot cast its skin is doomed to die.

The man who cannot evolve from his past, is doomed to regret it. 
.

Coexisting with wolves offers benefits far beyond just humans and wolves.

Coexistence = healthy ecosystems, biodiversity enhancement, natural population regulation, cultural enrichment, sustainable ecotourism opportunities, and ethical, long-term conflict resolution. An increasing body of scientific research shows us that lethal methods are often less effective than non-lethal solutions in reducing conflict and, in some cases, can actually increase conflict. üê∫üåé

Wolves, by nature, generally maintain a cautious distance from humans. Their inherent fear of people serves as a vital function in keeping wolves safe and subsequently reduces potential conflicts between wolves and people. There are rare instances when wolves may lose this fear, typically due to habituation or associating humans with a food source, which is an important reminder to keep wildlife wild.

Project Coyote advocates for collaboration among stakeholders with a shared objective of fostering coexistence between people, farm animals, and wildlife. Resources, such as our Ranching With Wildlife Program, now exist to educate and support ranchers and farmers in adopting evolving techniques that ensure animal safety through the utilization of predator-friendly management tools. While domestic animal losses are an unfortunate aspect of ranching, most stem from disease, adverse weather conditions, or birthing complications. The combination of sound animal husbandry practices and strategic non-lethal predator control methods can significantly reduce wildlife conflicts. üê∫üå±üêÑ

Maintaining a balance between the needs of wolf populations and human communities is crucial for successful coexistence. The key lies in the management of human-wolf conflicts through education and responsible practices. #WolfAwarenessWeek

BOGOTA, Colombia
A day after Colombian President Gustavo Petro threatened to suspend relations with Israel due to their decision to halt security material exports to Colombia in response to his Middle East crisis stance, Foreign Minister Alvaro Leyva asked Israeli Ambassador Gali Dagan to "apologize and leave".

Using his X account, Leyva demanded respect for the president and accused Dagan of being "rude."
‚ÄúThe history of universal diplomacy will record as a milestone the senseless rudeness of Israel's ambassador in Colombia towards President Gustavo,‚Äù Leyva published on X. ‚ÄúShame on him. He should at least apologize and leave. Intelligence is confronted with intelligence. There are States at stake.‚Äù

This statement from Leyva intensifies an already elevated state of diplomatic tension between Colombia and Israel.
The Israeli Ministry of Foreign Affairs had previously summoned Colombia's ambassador and reprimanded her for "hostile and anti-Semitic" comments by President Petro, who has refused to condemn the recent attack by Hamas on Israel, despite pleas from the Israeli government and the United States to do so.

I have so many words and none feel worthy of the moment, but something is vibrating madly in the unknowable core of my chest right now.

I don‚Äôt have a fresh take on war, conflict, religion, or right vs wrong that feels relevant, at the moment. Maybe I will, maybe I won‚Äôt. There are countless opinions thoughtful and otherwise circulating. At the moment I have nothing to add to that conversation.

I‚Äôve been watching in horror as you have. In the hideously beautiful midst of my own grief work after helplessly watching our beautiful son die to some unseen and unknown condition, I exist now each day with a partially cracked-open heart.

When I watched this particular clip, that crack burst open, tens of thousands of years wide.

I simply cannot imagine the feeling of being in this position, my kid on a ventilator, certain to die if moved, and worrying simultaneously about a bomb falling on the hospital because of religious extremist hate. Because of the insidious cycle of revenge. Because of blind fear of some god‚Äôs petty retribution. Because of whatever the justification of the day is.

I can‚Äôt do anything to help these innocent children, just as I couldn‚Äôt ultimately help ours. And no, our situations are not at all the same. I am aware and understand my privilege to be able to post this.

My words won‚Äôt change their lives, or their fate, or probably anything at all in their situation.

I simply want to say to you, and anyone this reaches that is in pain, or the throes of existential, acute grief, or in some dangerous and impossible position right now:

I see you. I feel with you. I love you. My heart breaks with you. I will not stand silently, idly by.

I don‚Äôt want a comment section here, but you are welcome to message me if you feel called.

I encourage you to express and act your own love and goodness into the spaces available to you, just as I encourage safe and healthy and mindful places to express the opposite.

The "window of tolerance" is a psychological concept that describes the optimal zone within which we can effectively process and manage our emotional and psychological experiences. It's like a comfort zone for our emotional responses, where we can cope and adapt to various situations.

In the context of what we are witnessing in Palestine at the moment, those who are directly affected by the conflict have been pushed outside of their window of tolerance. Their experiences go far beyond what any human should have to endure, pushing them into states of extreme distress, fear, and pain. They are essentially in "fight or flight" mode, which means their bodies and minds are in a heightened state of stress, ready to either confront the danger or flee from it.

The intense grief and violence they endure overwhelm their coping mechanisms, making it difficult to find a sense of stability and emotional safety amid the chaos and bloodshed.

For those of us who are watching the events unfold from a distance, we may also find ourselves pushed outside of our window of tolerance, but perhaps in a different way. The constant stream of distressing news, images and stories can be emotionally overwhelming, leading to feelings of helplessness, anger and despair. 

Witnessing such widespread suffering and injustice can make us feel helpless or powerless, pushing us into a "freeze" mode. In this state, we may become emotionally and physically depleted, finding it challenging to motivate ourselves or continue with daily life.

The challenge, then, is to find a way to stay within our window of tolerance, even in the face of such traumatic events. This involves caring for our mental and physical health, finding solace in prayer and duaa, staying connected with our local communities, and taking positive actions such as raising funds and awareness where we can. 

It's crucial to acknowledge that everyone has a different level of tolerance, and what one person can endure, another may not. Be mindful of the emotional toll that witnessing such trauma is taking on you and invest in coping strategies to stay within your healthy emotional zone.

#globalcrisis #freepalestine #windowoftolerance

Police in Brussels on Tuesday morning shot a man suspected of carrying out the fatal shooting of two Swedish nationals in the city center on Monday night. Interior Minister Annelies Verlinden later confirmed that the suspect was killed after police encountered him in a cafe in the Belgian capital's Schaerbeek neighborhood. "The perpetrator of the terrorist attack in Brussels has been identified and has died," Verlinden wrote on social media. Belgium had raised the security alert status of Brussels to the highest level in the wake of the attack, ramping up police presence. Officers tracked down the suspect after an intensive manhunt. 
The automatic rifle found close to the person who was shot was the same weapon as the one used during the Monday evening attack, Interior Minister Verlinden told broadcaster VRT. Two Swedish nationals were shot dead in the attack and a third one was wounded. The suspect fled the scene in central Brussels after the shooting, as a football match between Belgium and Sweden was about to start. The match was subsequently called off. The suspect, who had identified himself as a member of the so-called "Islamic State" terror group, claimed responsibility in a video posted online. Earlier, Belgian Prime Minister Alexander de Croo said the suspect was a man of Tunisian origin who was living in Belgium illegally. The attacker was known to police in connection with people smuggling. He had unsuccessfully sought asylum in Belgium in November 2019. 
Source: AFP, Reuters

A better filter‚Ä¶

Too many of us give lip service to excellence and doing work that matters but then walk the path of least resistance.

We filter our days through a series of micro-decisions to avoid conflict and confrontation, effort and struggle, pain and failure.

Then we wonder why we‚Äôre in the same anxious, dissatisfied place we were a week ago, a month ago, a year ago‚Ä¶

Here‚Äôs a simple filter to fix this problem:

* Is it easy?

If the answer is ‚Äúyes,‚Äù it‚Äôs the wrong project, activity, path, etc. 

If you want to grow as a leader, salesperson, parent, lover, etc. ‚Äúeasy‚Äù should be a negative filter. 

Nothing worth doing is easy, not over the long term‚Ä¶

Purpose. Happiness. Satisfaction. These are the result of struggle, of working through pain despite fear and anxiety. 

Easy is a trigger warning that you‚Äôre on the wrong path‚Ä¶ 

‚Ä¶or that you‚Äôre not working hard enough, not committed, or living someone else‚Äôs life. 

Easy is for the ordinary. 

Ordinary people want easy. They seek it out. Everything they do is to make life easy‚Ä¶ 

Are you ordinary?

That is an honest question. 

Because for some people, ordinary is completely acceptable, and that‚Äôs fine.

These people would rather not deal with the pain and struggle of a meaningful life‚Ä¶a life spent, much like Sisyphus, pushing rocks uphill in the effort of work that matters.

These ordinary people seek refuge in Netflix, drugs, porn, excuse-making, and any number of other instant gratification distractions meant to dull the pain the regret buried deep down in their souls.

I just didn‚Äôt think that was you. 

Wait‚Ä¶that‚Äôs not you? You don‚Äôt accept ordinary? You feel called to make a dent in the world?

Then why the f*ck would want anything to be easy?!

Find what‚Äôs hard in your life, and then take Ryan Holiday‚Äôs advice, ‚ÄúThe obstacle is the way.‚Äù

That hard conversation with your lover; have it today

Writing that book you can‚Äôt get out of your head; start typing today

Building muscle and taking control of your health; push some f*cking iron around today.

If it‚Äôs not hard, it‚Äôs most likely meaningless.

‚Ä¶and why waste your life on meaningless stuff?

Seek out hard things.

This is the way.

IN THE SILENCE OF DECAY
Pinter, P.I #1

By Lisa Boyle @lisaboylewrites 

For @suzyapprovedbooktours

Out Oct. 24, 2023

I‚Äôve read Lisa‚Äôs historical fiction Paddy series so I was excited to see how she does with a genre switch into mystery. I can tell you she did AMAZING.

This is a multilayered and atmospheric mystery set in 1979 New Mexico.  It‚Äôs told in multiple points of view (like about 7) which I really enjoyed. It mixes some true life events with a fictional mystery and fictional characters.

The two main characters are James and Molly, a father and his fourteen year old daughter. James is an ex Army investigator who is now a truck driver. Molly comes to start living with James after her mother dies. I enjoy the way that Lisa writes about this very new father/daughter relationship.

The book takes place on and near a Navajo reservation so the reader gets a behind the scenes look at the politics that goes on there.

The Vietnam War plays a role in the story which is very interesting for me because I was a child during the later years of that conflict.

The mystery itself which is about a woman who is found dead by suspected overdose outside the reservation is great and all the characters add to the telling of the plot.

I look forward to reading the next installment of Pinter, P.I.

Our client F was taught from a young age that rest and play is laziness, and that productivity and good grades are what make her parents approve of her.

Her mother would frantically storm into her room when she was playing with her toys and demand that she do something "useful" around the house.

F learned that not being productive was bad.

Fast forward to a Saturday morning, when her husband is playing video games.

F feels her blood start to boil.
How could he be so lazy?
Doesn't he see that I'm running around the house cleaning up?
Did I marry the wrong person?

Since F has learned to reject the part of herself that desires rest and play, she can only see her husband's video game playing as a major flaw.

She believes that he is the problem and if he would just be more productive, she wouldn't feel so triggered...

This caused so much anxiety and conflict in her relationship.
She didn't want to be critical toward him, but she felt like she didn't have another option.

Through our work, F learned in her BODY that it was safe to rest and play.
She embraced the part of herself that she believed was "bad."

This completely shifted her approach toward her husband and his enjoyment of Saturday morning video games. She could now see her husband's light, playful demeanor as a reminder to not be so productive and serious all the time.

She even picked up a playful hobby of her own!

‚ÄòThe European Union had its chance to be the voice of peace and compromise. Instead, we sought photos and poses. We looked to side only with one side, even when we knew that retaliation meant more death and destruction.‚Äô 

Addressing Metsola, Farrugia said that the EU has no power or mandate, from Malta or elsewhere, to give their support to Israel‚Äôs offensive. The EU, he said, should be attempting to bring the two sides to the table and stop the fighting immediately. 

‚ÄòNot trying to paint a pretty picture of revenge by Israel on innocent people. Nothing good comes out of a war. No violence on innocent lives is justifiable. This is what our representatives in the EU should be saying and working for.‚Äô 

This comes after EP President Metsola, along with Commission president von der Leyen visited Israel to show their support following the attacks.

In a speech addressed to the plenary, Metsola condemned the mass murder, kidnappings, rapes, torture and mutilations carried out by Hamas. 

‚ÄòEven in the darkest of times, our Parliament has always and will always push for a fair two-state solution that is equitable and just. We will always push for a sustainable and lasting peace. Sadly, the vile actions of Hamas terrorists have pushed this prospect further away.' 

‚ÄòOur focus must remain on ensuring that the hostages kidnapped are released unconditionally, that humanitarian aid reaches those in need, that civilians are not targeted, that safe corridors are maintained', said Metsola.

#MaltaDaily

this week was hard. heavy. intense. 

but it was even harder for my Jewish friends, Muslim friends, Palestinian friends, and Israeli friends. i‚Äôve done my best to check in with them, but it doesn‚Äôt seem enough. 

i know this post isn‚Äôt going to make everyone happy, but it isn‚Äôt supposed to, and it‚Äôs where i‚Äôm at without waver. 

if you haven‚Äôt taken the time to learn about the Israeli-Palestinian conflict, the video by @voxdotcom i mentioned in Inclusive Strategies workbook is in my bio. 

as mentioned in my stories, this video was created in 2016. So much more has happened since then, obviously. Please do your own research and be vigilant of information going through your feeds right now.

if you have the workbook, you can scan the QR code or click the link in the interactive pdf on page 43. 

if you don‚Äôt have it, i will not be selling it for the sake of this conflict, simply because there‚Äôs so many more people you could learn from on this topic better than me. my one page in my workbook does not do the 75 years this conflict has unfolded into justice. 

my friends over at @jewishvoiceforpeace is one of the groups with so many resources and connections to work from. please give them a follow. 

i am leaving my comments on, but please know that if you showcase any anti-semitism, islamophobia, or any level of discrimination on this post, you will be blocked and your comment will be removed. 

there is no room for hate here. there is no room for the justification of genocide.
there is only space to learn, myself included.

to everyone who is hurting because of this, i am so deeply sorry, and please know i hold so much love and space for you.

Enneagram Type Nines, the Peacemakers, embody a parenting style marked by warmth, acceptance, and a steady presence. Their homes often become a safe haven where each family member feels unconditionally loved and accepted just as they are. Nurturing by nature, Type 9 parents foster a harmonious environment where their children are encouraged to grow without judgment.

Yet, every strength comes with its flip side. Their aversion to conflict might mean that Nines sometimes avoid tough conversations, and their accommodating nature could potentially morph into neglect of their own needs and desires. The peace they so cherish might at times deter them from addressing necessary disputes and from asserting their own boundaries. At times, their desire to maintain harmony may also lead them to reluctantly say 'yes' when a 'no' might be more beneficial. 

Type 9 parents (or those who were raised by a Type 9), how does this resonate with you? Share your stories and thoughts below! üí≠

My mother is Pahari, from the hills in India, and #Dussehra is a significant celebration in that area. We would go to the local mandir, where I fondly remember seeing the Ravana Dahan, the effigy burning, symbolizing the victory of good over evil. This story and the triumph of Sri Rama over Ravana greatly influenced how I view conflict and the concept of conquering evil.
.
Our family's celebrations have evolved, particularly with my Gujarati wife. We now participate in garba and dandiya events, and watching my daughters join in, including the Arati and devotional aspects, is a wonderful experience. Passing down the tradition to my children, especially during Navaratri, with its focus on the Feminine Divine, is very meaningful to me.
.
In America, the challenge lies in synchronizing our celebrations with the regular calendar due to work and school obligations. The @HinduAmerican has been instrumental in supporting those who need to take time off by providing resources and templates for communicating with schools and employers. Their educational resources have been invaluable for celebrating these festivals in schools and sharing our traditions.
.
I hope for greater awareness and understanding of these traditions in the future. While Diwali is more recognized, #Navaratri and Dussehra deserve similar recognition. It's important that we're understood not only as a community that celebrates with dances but also as one that reveres the Divine.
.
Being part of the HAF community and witnessing its growth has been a truly amazing experience, and I'm excited for the future and the impact we can make.
.
Samir Kalra is a Managing Director of the Hindu American Foundation.
.

If you feel like you are losing your mind right now, do not panic. Take a deep breath. Losing your mind feels terrifying at first because you are losing/letting go of ideas and concepts that you‚Äôve held your whole life. 
Awakenings of the soul don‚Äôt always look pretty. It was quite the opposite for me. I fought everything. I felt like I was going crazy, dying, suffocating, screaming on the inside, and I was so uncomfortable in my own being. 
I was realizing how infinite the soul was, but the ideas in my head all held limitations so my true nature was met with resistance. There was a major internal conflict causing so much tension. I was trying to use my mind to escape my mind. Only adding to it all. 
But losing my mind would be the beginning of my spiritual journey. Allowing me to connect to a deeper place within my being that is beyond the mind. I still forget and get lost in the thinking mind, but I am much quicker to become aware of that now and bring my attention back to the present moment. 
So if you feel lost, scared, trapped or going crazy do not panic. I truly believe this is all a part of the spiritual journey. Finding out who we are not, so that we may know who we are. Be kind to yourself. You are right where you are supposed to be.

From Beni to Oicha, Butembo to Rutshuru and Fataki. In the towns of East Congo, peace activists support their communities in the midst of relentless conflict, 2022. They speak with local garrisons, bring supplies and find shelter for those displaced by fighting. They track which towns may be safe for civilians to return to, sharing scarce information from remote red zones.
They form groups to source cash and bring assistance for widows of dead troops, also keeping an eye on their sons and brothers to prevent recruitment by rebel groups. Some of this work is dangerous, almost all of it is unsung.

#ArtFairPH/Projects 2023: "Delusions of Grandeur Woke Farm" by Pow Martinez (@_powmartinez_)

Known for paintings that are once grotesque yet described as ‚Äúindelibly beautiful,‚Äù #PowMartinez continues the ‚Äúbad art‚Äù tradition in Philippine contemporary art popularized by such notables as Manuel Ocampo and Jason Oliveira. Characterized by lurid colors, bold strokes, and elements of the uncanny, his surreal scenes constitute a critique of modern life, in which figures‚Äîusually freaks, monsters, and outsiders of society‚Äîperform seemingly banal tasks against a mishmash of elements, seeming to extract normalcy from the disarray. Martinez challenges the viewer to consider their relationship with his works, particularly the imposition of meaning onto something that resists such an attempt. His every work may be seen as an invitation to be at ease with the disorder, especially in such a socio-political climate where even ‚Äúrealities‚Äù can be manufactured.

While Martinez paints otherworldly scenarios, he draws inspiration from recent events, watching YouTube documentaries on conflict zones and the climate crisis. The news of the day is then refracted through the artist‚Äôs untamed imagination, which then churns out complex forms, shapes, and textures. His subjects, in relation to their surroundings, give off hyper-focused expressions that evoke a sense of detachment. Such an attitude may be the condition‚Äîor the predicament‚Äîof living in the moment, when the only certainty seems to be the annihilation of the human species.

Minister Ron Hoenig is entirely right.

The chant of ‚ÄúFrom the River to the Sea, Palestine Will Be Free‚Äù, a rallying cry long used by Hamas, is completely reprehensible.

The chant is calling for a Palestinian state extending from the Jordan River to the Mediterranean Sea, territory which encompasses the State of Israel.

In other words, these protesters are calling for a Palestinian state instead of - not in addition to - Israel.

The State of Israel has a right to exist and her people deserve to live in safety. Calls that say otherwise, including this chant, are preventing Israelis and Palestinians from resolving the conflict and living in peace.

The West was understandably shocked and appalled by Hamas's massacre in Israel. Nothing can justify or rationalize such a display of cruelty. 

Neither the continuing occupation of the West Bank since 1967, with its attendant violence, nor the rise of Jewish Supremacism, once relegated to the fringes of Israeli society before being whitewashed by Prime Minister Benjamin Netanyahu, nor the abandonment of Palestine by the Arab countries, the United States and Europe.

On the other hand, these three factors cannot be ignored as Israel's ground operation creeps ever closer; they determine Israel's response.

Israeli society is reeling from the horror of the terrorist operation. Discredited for failing to prevent the attack, the government and army are under immense pressure. It must react. Punish. It must strike. 

Israel faces a precipice. The Hamas attack is also a trap. It destroys the deterrence at the heart of Israel's security doctrine, forcing it to radically review its traditional militarized management of the enclave. 

The premeditation of this attack is a disproportionate and indiscriminate response, in disregard of the two million civilians living in Gaza. The price Israel could pay for a large-scale operation goes beyond the human toll. Its alliances, regional security and very soul are at stake.

That Israel has the right to defend itself does not answer the question of the purpose of a ground invasion. The law of retaliation cannot take the place of military strategy.

Without even mentioning the phenomenal cost in civilian lives that lies ahead, no one on the Israeli side has the time or desire to consider what will come next. What will emerge from the ashes, if not more fire?

I have family and friends in Israel. I know no one has been untouched by Hamas‚Äô violent acts. There is never an excuse for terrorism. 

And, what about the terror, systematic dehumanization that the IDF and Israeli government has imposed on Palestinians for decades? 

I do not, cannot stand with the right-wing, authoritarian government of Israel just as I could not, would not stand with the U.S. government in 2003 during the invasions of Iraq and Afghanistan. My activism did not make me any less American. Why does my activism against the inhumane policies of Israel continue to call my Judaism into question? 

We are a generous, thoughtful, values-rich people. But I am now questioning this community‚Äôs ability to hold nuance and act on our values. 

I am questioning its ability to hold people like me, desperately in search of solace and a community where we can say no to Israeli death but we can also question and even object to the actions of the Israeli government, which commits acts of violence in the name of the Jewish people. 

We are staring down the barrel of an ethnic cleansing in Gaza as vengeful Israeli tanks get into position. Where are our voices now? Do our Jewish values not tell us that violence should not beget violence, that flattening Gaza won‚Äôt bring back the dead nor defeat Hamas nor bring peace? 

The only thing that will bring peace is centering each other‚Äôs humanity, and while the conflict is complicated, at the end of the day, it‚Äôs actually quite simple. We would be in a different place today if we had built systems that recognized rather than denigrated Palestinian humanity.

Join us in welcoming WCC‚Äôs Chief 

Named in honor of United States Army Chief Warrant Officer Eugenio Rivera 

United States Army Chief Warrant Officer Eugenio Rivera was drafted from his hometown of Bayamon, Puerto Rico, in 1952. He went on to complete his basic training as a U.S. Army Engineer at Fort Dix, New Jersey, before being stationed in Germany and France. Chief Warrant Officer Rivera was deployed to serve two tours of duty in the Vietnam Conflict, where he was stationed in Mekong Delta in southern Vietnam. On his second deployment, Chief Warrant Officer Rivera had the opportunity to serve as an advisor to the South Vietnamese Army. In addition to his two tours in Vietnam, he also deployed to Korea as well as South and Central America. 

In his 32-year-long career, he served at duty stations throughout Panama, Washington, D.C., Germany, Maryland, and California before retiring from the U.S. Army in 1984. Following his retirement, he worked for the U.S. Army at the Defense Language Institute at Presidio of Monterey. There, he continued to support his fellow Service Members to teach them the languages necessary for the current conflicts of the world. Chief Warrant Officer Rivera instilled in his family a great honor for Military Service and the values he learned during his career in the U.S. Army. To this day, his son Ron Rivera (@riverboatronhc), head coach of the Washington @commanders , continues to honor his service by proudly wearing CW4 on his hat during salute to service weeks. Ron also serves as an advocate for his players and team members to continue to give back to Service Members and Veterans. 

It is with great pride that we name #WCCsChief in honor of United States Army Chief Warrant Officer Eugenio Rivera

US Secretary of State Antony Blinken confirmed on Monday that the day-long trip to the region will reaffirm America's support for one of its closest allies.

"He's coming here at a critical moment for Israel, for the region, and for the world, " Blinken said, adding that "the president will reaffirm the United States solidarity with Israel and our ironclad commitment to its security."

White House National Security Council Spokesperson John Kirby told reporters that Biden will "reaffirm our solidarity with Israel, and he will look forward to getting an update from Israeli officials about their strategy and the pace of their military operations. He'll certainly expert to hear from Israel what they believe they need to continue to defend their people, and so that we can continue to work with Congress to try to meet those needs."

Biden is scheduled to talk with Israeli officials about the nearly 200 hostages that Hamas is believed to be holding in the Gaza Strip, and learn additional information about the situation and coordinate efforts to secure their release, Kirby said.

The president will also travel to Amman, Jordan, where he'll meet with Palestinian Authority President Mahmoud Abbas, as well as Jordan's King Abdullah, and Egyptian President Abdel Fattah El-Sisi. There, they'll discuss the humanitarian needs of Gaza's civilians.

"Innocent civilians are innocent civilians," Kirby said. "And none of them, no matter what side of the line they live on, or how they call themselves or how they worship deserve to be victims of armed conflict. As I've said before, the number of appropriate civilian casualties is zero. And we have been nothing but consistent about that."

The trip will be just one day long, but "there's an awful lot on the agenda," Kirby said. "Again, reiterating that Israel has the right to defend itself and to go after these Hamas terrorists, and that the United States will continue to support them."

"I would remind that Hamas is deliberately putting innocent civilians at greater risk by setting up road blocks, not letting them move, putting up commanding control headquarters in tunnels underneath their homes and schools and hospitals."

Luke and I were able to go on a trip to Jordan with my parents and some of my siblings. We were supposed to spend 2 days in Petra then make our way into Israel for a ‚ÄúHoly Land‚Äù trip. However, the morning we left for our trip was when the 1st attacks happened in Israel. When we got to Jordan, our guide was very confident that we were far enough away from the conflict that it would not interfere with our trip. However, a couple days in we learned that the conflict was escalating and most of our Israel plans were being cancelled‚Ä¶ including our return flights out of TelAviv. So we had to cut our 2 week trip in half and scramble to get flights out of Amman with everyone else trying to flee the country. 
Though it was not the trip we planned, it was still amazing. The Jordanian people were so kind, happy to see us there and we felt safe the entire time we were in their country. We are hopeful we will get to go back someday and finish our trip but for now, we are safely home with our kids.

There are plenty of jobs that are dangerous, and journalism can be one of them.

We've already seen that during the horrific conflict between Hamas and Israel where journalists have been seriously injured and one killed.

But it's also happened closer to home.
The killing of five Australian newsmen in Balibo, East Timor on October 16th, 1975 was horrific. 

Two television teams, from Channels Seven and Nine were assigned to investigate what would ultimately be an invasion into East Timor by Indonesian soldiers, only to die before they could get their stories out.

The truth of what happened to them has taken years to uncover, because both Indonesian and Australian governments have kept much of what they know underwraps.

It is a shameful history that still today is mired in secrets and sins.

Tonight on @underinvestigationau we'll reveal the confidential files and peel back the layers that have covered the truth of what happened to five newsmen, murdered because they were doing their job.

On 17th October, the 11th day of Israel's bombardments on the besieged Gaza Strip, Israel bombed the Al Ahli hospital in Gaza, killing more than 500 people including patients, doctors & those seeking refuge.

Gaza is home to 2.3 million Palestinians (1.1 million children) and is one of the world's most densely populated places. Israel has held it under siege for 17 years. In the last 11 days Israel has dropped thousands of bombs on the imprisoned population, estimated to be the equivalent force of a quarter of a nuclear bomb. Human rights experts have also confirmed the use of the internationally-banned weapon, white phosphorus.

On 15 October 2023, over 800 scholars and practitioners of international law, conflict studies and genocide studies signed a public statement warning of the possibility of genocide being perpetrated by Israeli forces against Palestinians in the Gaza Strip.

Signatories include prominent Holocaust and genocide studies scholars.

"As scholars and practitioners of international law, conflict studies and genocide studies, we are compelled to sound the alarm about the possibility of the crime of genocide being perpetrated by Israeli forces against Palestinians in the Gaza Strip. We do not do so lightly, recognising the weight of this crime, but the gravity of the current situation demands it."
