What is Peace and Conflict studies (PACS)? üìöüí≠

PACS is an interdisciplinary program that focuses on systemic, as well as grassroots, perspectives on organized violence, conflict resolution and the concept of peace. The programme covers questions such as: how does organized violence arise, how can violence be countered, what role do international organizations and civil society play in the work for peace both locally and globally?

These questions are not only interesting to discuss, but also extremely relevant in today's society. Both internationally and locally.

/Kamilla

It is easy to think that if you simply avoid the conflict in your relationship, it does not exist. This is actually a coping mechanism, typically stemming from earlier experiences of conflict that didn‚Äôt go well, avoidant attachment style, or childhood trauma, etc. ‚Å†
‚Å†
Some reasons we may avoid conflict may include: people-pleasing, fear of abandonment , personal insecurities, fear of the relationship ending, not knowing how to communicate when someone is upset with you, etc. Because we enter new relationships carrying the wounds of our past, it is always a good idea to consider individual therapy to heal these wounds so we show up as our best selves to our partner. The goal is not to be perfect, but to understand why we may have stronger reactions to certain situations and how to cope with these reactions. ‚Å†
‚Å†
If you are someone who experienced trauma and find that it negatively affects your relationship, do not feel like you are doomed. Sometimes our deepest need in our romantic relationship is what we didn‚Äôt get as children. So our romantic relationships can be a portal into healing traumas. üíö‚Å†
‚Å†
In healing,‚Å†
‚Å†

"I have tried to give a voice through art to the tragic events involving journalists in the course of armed conflicts. I did it for the Russo-Ukrainian conflict, and since yesterday, I have started doing it for the ongoing conflict. The @committeetoprotectjournalists is investigating all cases of journalists killed, injured, detained, or missing. The situation is particularly critical for journalists in #Gaza, tasked with documenting the conflict despite the high risks posed by Israeli troop incursions, devastating Israeli airstrikes, disrupted communications, and prolonged power outages.

As of October 16, at least 12 journalists have been reported as victims of the conflict, with over 4,000 deaths on both sides since October 7, the start of the conflict. The list includes 10 Palestinian journalists, one Israeli, and one Lebanese. Eight other journalists are reported as injured, while three are reported as missing or detained. CPJ is also investigating reports of threats to journalists and damage to various media offices.

Sherif Mansour, the Coordinator of CPJ's Middle East and North Africa program, emphasizes that journalists are civilians engaged in crucial work during crises and should not be targeted by conflicting factions. Mansour highlights that their work requires significant sacrifices, and all involved parties must take measures to ensure their safety.

The list published by CPJ, based on information from the region and media reports, includes the names of the involved journalists. However, it is not always clear whether they were covering the conflict at the time of their death. CPJ continues to regularly update the list as it investigates the circumstances of individual cases."

I get it (believe me). Anxious/avoidant dynamics are hard af.
¬†
But dating someone with the same attachment style as you isn‚Äôt the fix it can feel like it is.

The goal is to move toward secure attachment, not to find a relationship in which you can ignore the work.
¬†
Image Description: Orange flowers on a branch are overlaid with a light salmon orange background. Each graphic has a thought written in a simple, white, sans serif font in the middle. Above each point is a white rectangle with a simple, black, sans serif font that says, ‚ÄúThink about it,‚Äù flanked on either side by a six-pointed star. Below each point is the same style, but has Melissa‚Äôs Instagram handle in the rectangle. The graphics read: (1) Anxious/avoidant dynamics are not the only difficult insecure attachment match‚Äù; (2) ‚ÄúThe anxious/avoidant trap gets a bad rap‚Äîfor good reason: it's deeply painful‚Äù; (3) ‚ÄúAll insecure attachment styles and relationships need work‚Äînot just anxious/avoidant couples‚Äù; (4) ‚ÄúRelationships between avoidants can feel safe and healthy: ‚ÄòFinally! Someone who doesn't want to process everything, so I can have peace and quiet.‚Äô But in reality, this dynamic can be harmful: it's driven by conflict avoidance, which is a recipe for disaster‚Äù; (5) ‚ÄúRelationships between anxious babes can feel safe and healthy: ‚ÄòFinally! Someone who wants to move at the same pace I do and is commitment-forward, so I can have security!‚Äô But in reality, this dynamic can be harmful: it's driven by abandonment fears, which is a recipe for disaster‚Äù; (6) ‚ÄúA partner with our same insecure attachment style can feel like a godsend‚Äù; (7) ‚ÄúIn feelings of comfort and safety, where are we avoiding the work we still have to do?‚Äù; (8) ‚ÄúIt is our responsibility to move toward secure attachment, even when our relationship doesn't ask us to‚Äù; (9) ‚ÄúOur attachment is not magically healed by a partner whose fears match ours‚Äù; and (10) ‚ÄúAsk yourself: What work does my partner and relationship give me permission to ignore?‚Äù

Have you ever had an authority figure tell you: ‚ÄúDo as I say, not as I do?‚Äù You lose a bit of respect for them after that, don‚Äôt you? They may even seem like a hypocrite if they aren‚Äôt living by the rules they‚Äôre giving.

For FOCUSED member and now ADHD coach, Natalie, this internal conflict led her to a big life change that you might not expect. She quit recreational marijuana use. But it wasn‚Äôt fellow smoking clients that led her to this decision. 

It was the fact that she was coaching vulnerability and asking people to open up and make bold changes in their lives to move forward and achieve their potential when she herself felt like she wouldn‚Äôt and couldn‚Äôt give up this one thing that she was desperately dependent on to feel good.

This week‚Äôs episode of I Have ADHD takes a unique perspective on cannabis use for adults with ADHD - one of honesty, no judgment, and a straightforward look at the pros and cons that the effects of this plant had on someone many of us can relate to.

I hope you listen in on this one and can walk away with these key messages:
The pain, stress, or tension you may feel is real and valid, and you are deserving of relief. It may even come in the form of cannabis.

For those of us with ADHD, we need to be mindful that we are more susceptible to substance use, abuse, and addiction. And when our mental health struggles are left undiagnosed, untreated, and/or unmedicated, we will inevitably find something to help us feel better as fast as possible. 

Numbing emotions or avoiding feelings is not a healthy way to deal with ADHD, no matter how tempting it may be to turn all the noise down in our heads and feel like our neurotypical friends for a minute.

Tune in to Natalie‚Äôs story, and I welcome your thoughts and personal experiences on this topic as we all strive towards health and wholeness living with ADHD.

Synopsis:

Sometimes unexpected paths lead to the best destinations.‚Ä®‚Ä®Highly sought after conflict photographer, relationship-averse Marley Cunningham thrives on adrenaline and the chaos of her nomadic life. But when the passion for her career starts to wane, she decides a hike far from the noise of life is the best way to shake the doubts from her mind and focus on what she wants. Spraining her ankle and being rescued by a handsome stranger and his pack of dogs is not part of the plan.
Big-hearted, reclusive Bennett Morgan has spent his life with two main goals, play professional football for a few years and then pursue medicine. Shortly after his football career begins, a catastrophic diagnosis shatters both goals in one fell swoop. Feeling lost for the first time, he packs up his life and two dogs and returns to the home he couldn‚Äôt wait to leave. It‚Äôs in the shadow of his past that he finds joy in starting a dog sanctuary.
After a rainstorm washes away the road to Bennett‚Äôs home, he is shocked to find Marley injured and alone on the secluded trail he walks the dogs on daily. From the moment she is hoisted onto his back, Marley is drawn in by Bennett‚Äôs kindness, strength and calm nature. Bennett quickly realizes that a bit more human connection in his life might not be such a bad thing, especially when that human is beautiful, courageous, complicated, Marley.
Through the patience and care of Bennett, Marley begins to explore her feelings for not just her career but to her shock, the man who rescued her. Bennett, on the other hand, must decide if embracing the present with Marley is worth it, even if the future is uncertain.

I write with a heavy heart about the latest, deadly escalation in the Israeli-Palestinian conflict. I share my deepest condolences for those who have lost loved ones and are traumatized by Hamas‚Äôs recent attacks on Israeli civilians, with over 1,400 people killed including children. I am moved by the powerful words of survivors like Noi Katzman whose brother Chaim was killed in the attacks and said: ‚ÄúThe most important thing for me and also for my brother, is that his death will not be used as a justification for killing innocent people.‚Äù (1)

I also grieve alongside those families who have lost loved ones in Palestine, with Israeli aerial bombardment killing to date more than 4,200 people including over 1,000 children and the spiraling humanitarian catastrophe. We must prioritize shared human dignity and empathy for all at risk in this conflict, especially children. I call upon President Biden and Secretary Blinken to listen to Israeli and Palestinian human rights organizations and to work with Israel‚Äôs government to ensure the release of hostages and pursuit of those culpable for the Hamas attacks without engaging in collective punishment and the killing of Palestinian civilians. (2) (3)

Constituents throughout the 16th Legislative District and the State of New Jersey are in mourning and we all must join to support one another through these heartbreaking times. Israelis and Palestinians deserve to live in peace and safety as do all the diverse communities in New Jersey. As a mother, I implore all parties to focus on our common humanity to heal and build the peaceful world our children deserve.

Sincerely,

ASSEMBLYWOMAN SADAF F. JAFFER

The situation in Gaza right now is as close to Hell as many of us could imagine. The evacuation of hospitals, critical utilities cut off, an enforced exodus to the south of the region and more dead and dying as a result of the most horrendous conflict in one of the most densely populated areas is hard to comprehend. 

The murder and mayhem visited on communities in Gaza and southern Israel must come to an end. The cycle of violence has to stop. The politics of force and violence can never secure a lasting peace. Violence inflicted on civilians, of the kind we‚Äôve seen this last week, is like a virus that affects and infects a society for generations. The only cure is the relentless pursuit of dialogue and peace between people even with the most historic enmity.

Saltwater crocodile expert and @ourANU PhD scholar Yusuke Fukuda says that most years there have been one or two fatal crocodile attacks in Queensland and the Northern Territory combined.

A spooky thing about saltwater crocodiles is that you can‚Äôt trust your senses that you‚Äôll see or hear a croc: they are experts at hiding under the water‚Äôs surface.

‚ÄúWater that is just two feet deep is enough for a four-metre crocodile to hide from you,‚Äù says Yusuke.

‚ÄúEven if he's only two metres away from your feet, you won‚Äôt see him.‚Äù

That‚Äôs why public education is key for human-crocodile conflict management in Australia.

The photograph is rich with detail about surgical operations in the Civil War. One detail we noticed is what we've highlighted here: a surgeon holds a piece of white muslin over the patient's face. He has administered anesthesia and is monitoring the patient as the surgery takes place. 

As with nearly all amputations performed during the conflict, this one was being performed using anesthesia - chloroform and ether were both widely available and nearly universally used.

Step into the captivating world of the 1851 Agidingbi Battle Crest, where history and symbolism intertwine to tell a fascinating tale. This emblem is a veritable treasure trove of heritage, offering a glimpse into the rich tapestry of Lagos.

To the left, stands the majestic Royal Eben, a symbol of traditional authority that reigns over Lagos. On the right, we have the Lagos Mace adorned with the State Coat of Arms, a representation of the governance that shapes the destiny of Lagos State.

Nestled on the badge is the royal cap of the idejo Chiefs, the true custodians of Lagos' land. These dignitaries have watched over the city's heritage for generations.

The four-part Crest unfolds like a meticulously crafted narrative. The Eyo, introduced in Lagos on February 20, 1854, commemorates the funeral of Oba Akitoye, a central figure in the 1851 Bombardment of Lagos Narrative. A story of courage, conflict, and change.

Beside it stands the notorious HMS Bloodhound, the British warship that left an indelible mark on Lagos in 1851, forever etched in history.

Descending to the left, you'll find the royal sword of Lagos, wielded by heroes like Oshodi Tapa, who fought valiantly to defend the city with their lives. A symbol of unwavering loyalty and bravery.

On the right, a reminder of the past - the cannon guns that gave birth to the name "Agidingbi." a living echo, resounds from the onomatopoeic sounds produced by the artillery guns fired by British forces during the 1851 invasion of Lagos.

Underneath the crest, a fascinating mosaic of meaning unfolds. Cowries, reminiscent of trade and prosperity, intermingle with the  Akoko leaves , a symbol of obaship and the enduring authority of the Lagos throne.

And lastly, the ropes of unity and the chessboard, tying together the diverse threads of Lagos' history into a harmonious tapestry of identity and heritage.

Join us at the official launch on the 28th of October, 2023, at the Red Door Gallery, 51B Bishop Oluwole V.I.

RSVP Now https://tix.africa/discover/agidingbi

PRESIDENT TINUBU FELICITATES FOREMOST TRADITIONAL RULER, OONI OF IFE AT 49

President Bola Tinubu congratulates Ooni of Ife and Co-Chairman of the National Council of Traditional Rulers of Nigeria (NCTRN), Oba Adeyeye Ogunwusi on the occasion of his 49th birthday.

The President expresses gratitude to His Imperial Majesty for his unflinching support to the administration and remarkable efforts in rallying Royal Fathers from across the nation.

As the revered custodian of Yoruba heritage, history, and traditions, the President acknowledges the invaluable role of Oba Ojaja II in preserving and passing down the cultural and spiritual practices of the Yoruba people.

''Kabiyesi, since ascending the throne of your ancestors, your leadership has been instrumental in conflict prevention and resolution; community development, as well as representing the interests and concerns of Nigerians, both at home and abroad.

''I look forward to the continued partnership with our esteemed Royal Fathers to propel our nation forward.

''May God bless the Imperial Majesty with long life and good health, and may his reign be a source of unity and prosperity," President Tinubu says.

Chief Ajuri Ngelale
Special Adviser to the President
